<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Tea Auction Set to Close in June 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The 163-year-old London tea
auction will permanently close in June 1988 because of dramatic
declining trading volume.
</P>
<P>
Robin Harrison, a member of the London Tea Brokers'
Association, was quoted by the Reuters as saying today: "It is
very sad. It is something of a very special ending but the writing
had been on the wall."
</P>
<P>
"It was not commercially viable and the volumes were too low.
We now must look forward," said Harrison, adding London tea
brokers will have to find new ways to sell tea to their clients.
</P>
<P>
Thompson, Lloyd &AMP; Ewart and Wilson, Smithett and Co. are the
only two brokers which are still engaged in the London weekly tea
auction.
</P>
<P>
The Tea Broker's Association said in a release last month that
the auctions will be held on a fortnightly basis after the end of
January until the last sale on June 29, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The first tea auction in London, organized by The East India
Company in 1679, became a weekly event in 1834. Nearly 50 percent
of Britain's tea imports originate from Kenya and Britain is the
world's biggest tea importer.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some of the world's major tea exporters
including Kenya, India and Sri Lanka, have opened their own tea
auctions, taking away the final straw of the London tea auction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
