<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian President Calls for Muslims' Solidarity, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez Al-Assad
Tuesday urged the Islamic world to close ranks and rally against
Israel's "aggression of Arab homelands."
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the summit of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) here, Al-Assad
expressed the hope that the OIC meeting be the starting point for
solidarity and unity of all Arabs and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the Arab delegations, Al-Assad described
Israel's occupation of Arab lands as the "most serious" common
danger and challenge facing the Muslim world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Arabs, who are bearing the brunt of "Zionist
aggressions," are actually fending off the Zionist dangers that
might jeopardize all Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad blasted Israeli occupation as "hostile designs against
Arab land, people and civilization." "The deeper we look into the
series of events and developments which have taken place in the
20th century, the clearer appears the volume of those hostile
designs," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also attacked foreign powers for support Israel, saying they
"sow seeds of dissension in Arab and Muslim lands."
</P>
<P>
"Any dissension in our ranks is a source of strength for
Israel and an opening for infiltration into Arab and Muslim
countries," warned the president.
</P>
<P>
He praised Iran for its support of the Arab nation and
its struggle against Zionist greed for the land, wealth and
resources of Arabs and Muslims, and for its dedication to
"raising high the banner of Islam."
</P>
<P>
The president arrived here Monday for the eighth Islamic
summit. Syria, which sided with Iran in its eight-year war
against Iraq, has kept good relations with the Islamic
republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
