<HEADLINE> Russia's "Big Four" Hold Talks on 1998 Draft Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 9 (Xinhua) - Russian President Boris Yeltsin
has begun talks with Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and
speakers of both chambers of the parliament on the 1998 draft
budget, the Interfax reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We still have some questions to sort out. At this stage we
have to continue working on the budget," the president said at the
start of the talks, dubbed the meeting of the "big four."
</P>
<P>
The president said the draft budget should be further revised
so that it could win support from the State Duma (lower house of
parliament) at its second reading there.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said at the talks that the government's most
urgent task is to ensure the passing of the budget.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the State Duma approved the first reading of the
government's 1998 draft budget after Yeltsin made a surprise visit
to the chamber to appeal for deputies' support.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky said Tuesday's
meeting also discussed the topics to be addressed at the
round-table talks scheduled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the December 11 talks would focus on land
reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
