<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ottawa to End Health Cuts to Provinces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Canada's federal government has
promised that it will guarantee at least 12.5 billion dollars (8.8
billion USD) a year in transfer to the provinces for health care,
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The initiative, a fiscal dividend from the successful fight
against deficit, ends a final round of cuts to health and social
programs in the country.
</P>
<P>
"It is the single most important, tangible result of the
cleanup of the nation's balance sheet," said Finance Minister Paul
Martin.
</P>
<P>
It also means the ruling Liberal Party has made good on an
election promise that they would guarantee the 12.5 billion
dollars starting in the 1998-99 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The government had originally projected a drop in the Canada
Health and Social Transfer (CHST) system to 11.8 billion dollars
in 1998-99 and 11.1 billion dollars in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
The increase marks a turnaround from a steady erosion of the
government's health spending over the past four years.
</P>
<P>
However, the 12.5 billion dollar in CHST transfers for this
year is still more than 7 billion dollars lower than the CHST
level in 1993-94, the reports noted.
</P>
<P>
Canada's provinces have been complaining about the deep cuts,
which they say hurt the health care systems and put more burden
onto the provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
