<HEADLINE> Report: Pay Gap Exists Between EU Women, Men </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A significant pay gap exists
between women and men in European Union (EU) member states, said
survey results released here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, by the EU's statistical office Eurostat, covers pay
in four countries -- Sweden, France, Spain and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Its data show that women's hourly earnings as a percentage of
those of men differ from 84 percent in Sweden to 73 percent in
France and Spain, and to just over 64 percent in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Compared with male managers, women managers are worse off. In
Britain, they get two-thirds the pay of their male counterparts.
</P>
<P>
"There is a noticeable trend ... in all four countries, that
the elder the age group of women is considered, the further they
fall short of the average male earnings," said the report.
</P>
<P>
Although women with a university degree may earn more money
than women with lower qualifications, they actually earn a smaller
percentage of the equivalent male earnings, it added.
</P>
<P>
However, women and men in lower-paid non-manual jobs, such as
clerks and shop assistants, are close to equal pay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
