<HEADLINE> Mugabe Expressed Confidence Over Zimbabwean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe, in a state of the nation address today, expressed his
confidence that the country would pull out of the current
economic setbacks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at parliament, Mugabe said Zimbabwe is expected to
register a low economic growth rate of 3.7 percent this year as
compared to 8.1 percent recorded last year.
</P>
<P>
The government is, however, committed to containing the level of
deficit to no more than five percent of the gross domestic
product by the year 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the Zimbabwe Program for Economic and Social
Transformation (ZIMPREST), the second five-year economic reform
which started this year, is meant to achieve macro economic
stability.
</P>
<P>
''During the life of ZIMPREST, inflation is expected to
decline to single digit levels, savings to reach at least seven
percent in real terms,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
The president called for conlective responsibility so as to
turn around the negative economic environment the country was
currently going through.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that drive to privatize and dispose of parastatals
would be intensified in the country.
</P>
<P>
To effect future privatization drive, Mugabe said, the
government intended to establish a privatization unit which would
undeertake the function of appraising valuating and negotiating
the sale of identified parastatals.
</P>
<P>
He announced that the government ministries will before the
end of this year publish mission statements as part of the civil
service reform program, and the presidential office will monitor
the implementation of cabinet decisions and coordinate government
policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
