<HEADLINE> China's Zhan Breaks 70kg World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHIANG MAI, Thailand, December 9 (Xinhua) -- China's Zhan
Xugang Tuesday lifted 195.5kg in the men's 70kg class
clean-and-jerk event at the World Weightlifting Championships to
set a new world record.
</P>
<P>
Zhan broke his own world record by half a kilogram set in the
1996 Atlanta Olympics. However, He failed to win the gold because
it was set outside official competition, and did not count towards
the official totals.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old registered 195kg, the same as Vanev Zlatan of
Bulgaria, who finished ninth at the Atlanta Olympics. But Zlatan
is 0.25kg lighter than Zhan, so he swept all three events in the
category, with a total of 355kg and the snatch of 160kg and
clean-and-jerk 195kg.
</P>
<P>
Zhan, was forced to settle for a trio of silver medals
(157.5kg, 195kg and 352.5kg), but his world record was the third
set by Chinese lifters since the start of the championships.
</P>
<P>
Hometown favourite Suta Khassaraporn, world record holder in
the women's 59kg clean-andjerk, won the gold medal in that event
but was disappointed with her lift of 117.5 -- far below her 125kg
record set in October at the Southeast Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
It was the first gold medal that Thailand has ever savoured at
the current tournament which started Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Khassaraporn also snatched 92.5 for a total of 210 to take the
silvers. Indonesian Potmawati took the two golds, with 97.5kg and
212.5kg respectively.
</P>
<P>
China, who has dominated last two day's women competition, did
not send its lifters to contest in the category.
</P>
<P>
A total of 210 men and 151 women are competing in the world
championships to be concluded Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
