<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Three New NATO Invitees Unprepared to Join </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Hungary, Poland and the
Czech Republic are profoundly unprepared to join the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), according to the latest
edition of the Defense News.
</P>
<P>
The weekly magazine quoted NATO's classified documents as
saying that the three countries which the alliance decided to
accept as new members are years away from having militaries that
are minimally functional.
</P>
<P>
The information are contradictory to the recent public
statements by the alliance and European and American government
officials.
</P>
<P>
NATO defense ministers, when meeting early this month, agreed
that the 16 allies need to transfer only 1.5 billion U.S.
dollars over 10 years to NATO's budget.
</P>
<P>
When addressing a general assembly in Paris of the Western
European Union on December 4, NATO's Secretary-General Javier
Solana said the cost estimate was based on a "very solid military
analysis."
</P>
<P>
The invitees' military infrastructure is "in a better condition
than we had expected and the emphasis is on training and
interoperability, not high-tech equipment," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Defense News reported that the scope and depth of the
problems identified in the documents cast doubts into the ability
of the three to upgrade their military sufficiently or quickly
enough to attain interoperability with NATO in the near term.
</P>
<P>
"The deficiencies also demand a frank examination in NATO
parliaments whether the alliance can fund the real cost of
integrating the three into its structures with the limited money
to be set aside for this undertaking," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The NATO's documents listed deficiencies of the three countries
in army, navy and air force "page after page," according to the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
The alliance's assessments reveal that vast swaths of the three
countries, military infrastructures, ranging from Poland's Navy
and ports to the Czech Republic's Air Force, are obsolete,
unsecured for communications and generally incompatible with NATO.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Poland, NATO said in its documents that the
country's Navy is "well below NATO standards" and none of its
ships is "capable for command and control of joint or combined
operations."
</P>
<P>
In its 32-page assessment of Hungary, the alliance noted that
interoperability between the Air Force's command and control
systems and those of NATO is "very difficult or impossible in the
near term." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
