<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Workers Protest Taxes Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of thousands of the
Zimbabwean workers today staged a nationwide demonstration,
protesting the Finance Bill which seeks to increase sales
tax and tariffs on electricity and fuel.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the Zimbabwean government hiked tax on goods and
services by 2.5 percent to 17.5 percent, electricity tariff from
five to 10 percent, and fuel prices also increased.
</P>
<P>
In Harare, the country's capital, business came to a
standstill as workers stayed away from work and took to
streets for the demonstration organized by the Zimbabwe Congress
of Trade Unions (ZCTU).
</P>
<P>
There was even heavier police presence outside government
buildings and other public buildings such as banks.
</P>
<P>
In some areas, youths from the high density suburbs who
joined in the march, turned violent as they taunted the travelling
public and motorists, throwing stones at riot police who reacted
by firing teargas.
</P>
<P>
Workers in nearly all of the country's major cities also held
the similar demonstrations, causing closure of the entire
commercial activity.
</P>
<P>
The ZCTU announced it would be convening a special general
council meeting to deliberate the nationwide mass protests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
