<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Longest Undersea Fiber Cable Put into Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The world's longest undersea
fiber-optic cable system, the first of a new generation of
high-capacity undersea cables, was put into service today.
</P>
<P>
Known as Fiberoptic Link Around the Globe (FLAG), the system is
organized and designed by Bermuda-based FLAG Limited and Bell
Atlantic Corporation with its headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
The cable is the logest man-made structure ever built,
stretching 28,000 kilometers and linking Europe and Asia by way of
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
With landing points in Japan, Korea, China (Shanghai and Hong
Kong), Malaysia, Thailand, India, the United Arab Emirates, Egypt,
Italy, Spain and the United Kingdom, FLAG offers approximately 75
percent of the world's population access to a broadband
superhighway intended to meet the soaring demand for international
communications services, acting chairman of FLAG Limited Daniel
Petri told a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The system can transmit more than 10 gigabits of digital
information per second -- the equivalent of 600,000 simultaneous
conversations -- over two fiber pairs and offer secure and reliable
transmission to regions previously dependent on satellites, Petri
said.
</P>
<P>
FLAG construction was built in 27 months at a cost of 1.5
billion U.S. dollars. The system goes into service with 66
international carriers as customers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
