<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Pledges to Protect EU Beef Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Labor government has
promised that it would deal firmly with those protesting British
farmers in an effort to protect beef imports from other European
Union (EU) countries.
</P>
<P>
British trade minister David Simon made the pledge in a letter
to the EU Internal Market Commissioner Mario Monti following nine
days of British farmers' demonstrations at British ports in
protest of cheap European beef.
</P>
<P>
Simon said in the letter that the British government "takes the
threat of disruption to trade extremely seriously."
</P>
<P>
"We strongly condemn the action of those demonstrators who have
disrupted traffic. We condemn the actions of those demonstrators
who have disrupted traffic," he said.
</P>
<P>
Simon stressed that the British government was confident that
British police officers would "deal firmly with any threatening
behavior intended to persuade drivers to discontinue their
journeys".
</P>
<P>
It was reported some Irish trucks carrying beef products have
been forced to return to Ireland over the weekend at many British
ports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
