<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FSA, PIA to Combine Pensions Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 9 (Xinhua) - The Financial Services Authority
(FSA) and Personal Investment Authority (PIA) Boards have agreed
to create a single integrated division responsible for the
regulatory work arising from the mis-selling of personal pensions
in Britain.
</P>
<P>
It is announced here today that the division will include the
PIA Pensions Unit; the PIA pensions review monitoring department.
</P>
<P>
The creation of a new financial regulator was announced by
Chancellor Golden Brown on 20 May; and the Financial Services
Authority was formally launched by him on 28 October.
</P>
<P>
Creation of the FSA will occur in two stages. Once the Bank of
England Bill comes into force, the FSA will acquire responsibility
for banking supervision.
</P>
<P>
At that point, staff employed by the Investment Management
Regulatory Organization, the PIA and the SFA will also transfer to
the FSA.
</P>
<P>
The new division has set target deadlines for reviewing firms
to complete all the cases in the pensions review by 1998.
</P>
<P>
There are a total of 615,000 cases currently under review. At
31 October 1997, 90,000 investors had accepted offers of redress
worth a total of 503 million pounds (804.8 billion US dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
