<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agricultural Production Down in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's agricultural sector
growth rate fell by two percent this year compared to 21.4
percent in 1996, due to the excessive rains in 1996/97, President
Robert Mugabe said today.
</P>
<P>
Presenting at parliament the 10th state of the nation address
since independence in 1980, Mugabe said tobacco output which is
the country's biggest foreign currency earner had declined this
year.
</P>
<P>
Production of flue-cured tobacco fell by 7.5 percent from
175,350 tonnes in 1996 while burley tobacco fell by 19 percent
from 4,631 tonnes.
</P>
<P>
Due to the uncertainty of the intensity, duration and coverage
of this year's rainy season, the government has taken steps to
mitigate the effects of a possible food shortage.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the manufacturing sector is estimated to register a
growth performance of 8.5 percent compared to four percent
registered in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"This reflects a consolidation of the growth momentum which
commenced in 1996. In order to further spur this growth every
effort is being made to source concessionary loans from external
sources for lending to the business community," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
The mining sector has on the other hand been adversely
affected by low international prices, rising costs of production
of nickel, copper and gold among the most affected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
