<HEADLINE> S. Leone Rejects Being Listed as Moslem State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The military government in
Sierra Leone today expressed "dismay" over the listing of Sierra
Leone as a Moslem state at the eighth summit of Islamic leaders
which opened in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
A statement broadcast on State Radio said, "Sierra Leone has
always been a multi-religious state where different denominations
have peacefully coexisted since independence in 1961".
</P>
<P>
It assured all Christians and Muslims that "the government
will never allow the nation to be labeled a Moslem state."
</P>
<P>
Deposed president Tejan Kabbah, the first Moslem president of
Sierra Leone, is attending the session. He visited Tehran on two
state visits in 1996.
</P>
<P>
During the visits, he signed a number of agreements which gave
Tehran extensive business interests in Sierra Leone's fishing and
agricultural industries and arrangements were underway for Iran
to take over the diamond industry when the civilian government
was overthrown. 
