<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agreement Reached on Disarmament in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The military junta of Sierra
Leone, the west African peacekeeping force ECOMOG and other
concerned parties in S.Leone have reached a 14-point agreement on
disarmament, government sources disclosed here today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was hammered out here on Monday at the end of a
meeting of the Disarmament Committee which is one of the three
technical committees set up under the Conkry peace agreement in
October to return Sierra Leone to democratic rule next April.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the 14-point agreement includes the selection
of sites for troops disarmament, visit and assessment of
disarmament sites, determination of troops to Task Force level
and coordination of disarmament efforts and resources.
</P>
<P>
The agreeemnt also covered "coordination and cooperation with
other committees serving under the Conakry peace agreement,
transportation of arms to central storage facilities, security
arrangements for disarmament and demobilization."
</P>
<P>
"The agreement is supported by all participants" including
ECOMOG, the People's Army and the civil defense groups such as
Kamajors, the sources said. But no mention was made of the fate
of the Sierra Leone Army.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Disarmament Committee, Bashiru Conteh of the
Sierra Leone Army said, "The meeting is the best session we have
had with ECOMOG."
</P>
<P>
According to Conteh, "after the visits of the committee to
bases in the western areas and the interior, a timeframe will be
set for an all-out disarmament in the country."
</P>
<P>
The Conakry peace plan had initially set December 1 for a
month long disarmament deadline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0025 </DOCNO>
