<HEADLINE> Arab Leaders Pessimistic on Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Arab leaders attending the
Eighth Islamic summit starting here today were pessimistic about
the Middle East peace process in view of Israel's hardline stance.
</P>
<P>
"There is no hope for the peace process because of the Israeli
hardline policies and Israel's refusal to implement the peace
agreements with Arab countries," Secretary-General of the Arab
League Ahmed Esmat Abdel Meguid said in an exclusive interview
with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Meguid accused the Israeli Likud government of bringing the
peace talks between Arab countries and the Jewish state into a
deadlock, making the Arab world losing hope of the future of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat told Xinhua at the summit hall that the peace
process can not be resumed unless international communities make
efforts to save the process and put more pressure on the Jewish
state.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process became one of the hot topics at
the summit of the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
Despite sharp differences over relations between Islamic
countries and Israel, almost all the participating OIC members are
against the Israeli stubborn attitude and aggressive nature
regarding the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the PNA and Israel were stalled earlier this
year because of the intransigent policies of Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu towards the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech at the inaugural session of the OIC summit
this afternoon, Arafat said that the peace cannot be realized
unless the occupied holy city of Jerusalem returns to its
legitimate owners as the capital of an independent Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
"Jerusalem is the city of peace and tolerance, it is the key to
a just, lasting and comprehensive peace, the peace of braves
which we all are looking for," the Palestinian leader said.
</P>
<P>
He called for solidarity and unity among the Islamic countries
in confronting Israel's arrogance and its practice to ignore the
right of the Palestinian people to freedom, independence and
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the OIC summit will be an
opportunity for the Islamic countries to overcome their
differences and close their ranks in their fighting against the
Israeli aggression. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
