<HEADLINE> Cohen Postpones Mideast Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen postponed his six-day trip to the Middle East,
stated to begin this weekend, because of continuing tension over
weapons inspections in Iraq, the Pentagon said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in Iraq remains unsettled at a time when we
are maintaining a significant force in the Gulf area and demands
continued monitoring," the Pentagon said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
After Iraq allowed U.N. weapons inspectors back to Baghdad on
Nov. 20, the United States raised new demands to inspect
so-called presidential area in Iraq but was refused by the Iraqi
government on the ground it was a way of encroaching sovereignty
and dignity. And Washington still is keeping its mighty forces,
including two aircraft carriers, in the Gulf ready to give a
military strike on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The other issue that Cohen chose to stay in Washington was
for preparation for decisions on any new NATO-led military force
in Bosnia next June and on whether U.S. troops might join such a
force.
</P>
<P>
"Since political guidance must be prepared by Dec. 18 for
military authorities to develop those options, Secretary Cohen
has decided to remain in Washington," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It was the second such postponement of an overseas trip by
Cohen in a month over the Iraq situation.
</P>
<P>
On Nov. 10, he put off a major 12-day trip to China and five
other Asian countries, scheduled to begin two days later.
</P>
</TEXT>
