<HEADLINE> WHO to Move Regional Headquarters' Services to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
will transfer "certain services" of its regional headquarters in
Brazzaville to Maputo next year, WHO representative to the
country Carlos Tiny announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Tiny has briefed Mozambican Premier Pascoal Mocumbi on the WHO
intention, and Mocumbi said Maputo welcomed the idea, the
Mozambique News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to Tiny, Mocumbi assured him during the meeting that
"when the WHO regional headquarters comes across difficulty, it
is the obligation of the Mozambican government to provide
assistance."
</P>
<P>
"It is expected that some services of our regional
headquarters will settle down in Mozambique next year," Tiny
said.
</P>
<P>
WHO African headquarters in Brazzaville was closed in the
midst of the army riots in mid 1997 when Congolese president
Pascal Lissouba was kicked out of the Congo by the forces loyal
to former President Denis Sassou-Nguesso.
</P>
<P>
Most of the services of the WHO regional headquarters have
been moved to Zimbabwe later. 
