<HEADLINE> UN Chief Recommends to Reduce MONUA Personnel as Planned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today recommended to reduce the military component of
the United Nations Observer Mission in Angola(MONUA) from its
current 2,500 to 1,750 by the first week of January, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, Annan said with the
completion of the quartering of the troops of the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), the military
component of MONUA will be Gradually downsized.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said the peace process in Angola
continues to be slow, with intermittent surges of UNITA
cooperation and long periods of stagnation following one another.
</P>
<P>
Annan said since his last report to the Security Council on
October 17, there has been no significant progress in the
implementation of the remaining tasks. He blamed both the Angolan
Government and UNITA, but in particular UNITA, for this
unsatisfactory state of affairs.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief noted several key provisions of the Lusaka
Protocol have not been completed, in particular the
demilitarization of the troops of UNITA, and the extension of
State Administration throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General urged UNITA to complete without further
delay the crucial tasks of demilitarization and extension of the
State of Administration throughout Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
