<HEADLINE> Egypt-Iran Relations Improving: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said today that the relations between Egypt and Iran, which
were severed 18 years ago, are now improving.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with an Egyptian TV program, Moussa, who is
currently leading Egypt's delegation to the Islamic summit in
Iranian capital Tehran, said "Egyptian-Iranian ties are improving,
while the differences between the two countries should be
eliminated or be dealt with."
</P>
<P>
Moussa is the first Egyptian foreign minister to visit Iran
after Tehran and Cairo broke off their diplomatic ties after Egypt
signed the David Camp Accord with Israel in 1979. But relations
have been warmed up in recent years, particularly in economic and
scientific cooperations.
</P>
<P>
Moussa described Iran as a significant country in the region,
adding the country has historical ties with the Arab countries in
general and Egypt in particular.
</P>
<P>
He called on former Iranian president Hashemi Rafsanjani Monday
on the sidelines of the summit, the biggest event Iran has hosted
since the Iranian Islamic Revolution of 1979.
</P>
<P>
In November, Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister for Arab-African
Affairs Seyyed Mohammad Sadr said that Iran is all set to resume
diplomatic ties with Egypt, but on condition that their views
concur on Israeli regime and the talks on the Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
Former Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati visited
Cairo last May to invite Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to
attend the Islamic summit.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said that Mubarak has expressed the hope that
Cairo and Tehran will develop military cooperation to confront
regional threat like the Israeli-Turkish military cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
