<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Report: 22 Million Refugees Facing Tougher Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 9 (xinhua) -- The 1997-1998 State of
the World's Refugees report, which was issued today here by the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) says that
life has never been tougher for the 22 million refugees under
UNHCR' responsibility.
</P>
<P>
The report says in many parts of the world, people who have
taken refuge in another country are being harassed, attacked and
even forced to return home. In some regions, refugees are being
pushed form one country to another, fleeing fighting or attacks.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR charges that rich nations are united in their
determination not to accept them. Governments are slamming the
door in the faces of people seeking asylum. They fear the
refugees, and see them as political, social and economic threats.
</P>
<P>
Assistant United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees Soren
Jessen-petersen stressed that all countries must protect refugees.
" the right to asylum must be preserved. Asylum is the best way to
safeguard human security and dignity and therefore remains
absolutely essential for humanitarian action."
</P>
<P>
In order to prevent displacement, the report recommends
measures to eradicate poverty, strengthen peace and bring to
justice those people who are responsible for forcing millions form
their homes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
