<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Says No to External Pressure on Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu declared today that his government will not
subject to any external pressure on the issue of carrying out
further troop redeployments in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference in the southern resort city of
Eilat, Netanyahu said no external pressure will influence Israeli
government on the process of making decisions on further troop
redeployments in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on media reports that the United States is
exerting pressure on Israel to carry out the delayed second phase
of the three-stage troop pullbacks in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is to hold another meeting with U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright in Belgium's capital Brussels next
Wednesday to discuss ways of advancing the Israeli-Palestinian
peace process, especially the second redeployment. During their
two meetings in Paris last week, Albright demanded Israel make a
more credible decision on the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu stressed that once Israel carries out the second
pullback, any additional handover of the West Bank should take
place within the framework of the final-status talks with the
Palestinians. He also dismissed the media reports about his
intention to hand over 6-8 percent of the West Bank in the second
pullback as "incorrect."
</P>
<P>
By making the statement, Netanyahu was apparently trying to
show to Israeli public that he will not subject to any U.S. and
other external pressure.
</P>
<P>
Israeli state television Channel I reported today that the
Israeli government is unlikely to come out with a concrete plan on
the second redeployment before the Netanyahu-Albright meeting next
week.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial committee charged with formulating the second
pullback and Israeli position on the permanent talks have held
three sessions already, but failed to reach an agreement so far
due to inner rift on the Israeli security interests in the
territories.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Israel Radio reported that
U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross has telephoned Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy to urge Israeli government to make a
timely decision on the further redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The report added that U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for
Near East Affairs Martin Indyk, who retired not long ago as the
U.S. Ambassador to Israel, will visit Israel, Jordan, Syria and
Lebanon next week to advance the stalled Israeli-Arab peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government is reportedly increasingly impatient with
Netanyahu for his handling of the peace process, especially the
delay in carrying out the second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Under signed agreements, Israel should have completed the
first two stages of the three-phase further redeployments in the
West Bank by early September, but it has delayed the pullbacks
due to dispute over the scope and terror bombings in Jerusalem in
July and September.
</P>
<P>
Itamar Rabinovitch, former Israeli Ambassador to the U.S.,
told Israel Radio that he expects Albright to increase pressure
on Israel if she does not get what she wants on the further
redeployment during next week's meeting with Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
He added that, however, because the current U.S. government is
a very friendly one toward Israel compared to the previous ones,
Washington will only apply pressure in a subtle and indirect
way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
