<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Rate Declines in Kenya Despite Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The anticipated heavy spending
for the December 29 general elections in Kenya is unlikely to
spark inflationary pressure, economists said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics compiled by the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK)
indicated that the month-on-month inflation rate for November
fell to 8.2 percent from 8.7 in October.
</P>
<P>
All political parties in this east African country are
expected to spend a lot of money during the campaign period, but
CBK officials said these would not lead to a growth in the volume
of money in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Election observers said last week that the amount of money
spent on elections would be in billions of Shillings with the
ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU) estimated to spend
over 5 billion Shillings (about 80 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Economists, however, pointed out that the money being spent by
political parties for campaigning would be part of the money
already in circulation, hence the total money supply would not
change.
</P>
<P>
"All that will happen is that the money which is in individual
bank accounts will be shifted to particular political parties..."
according to a leading economist.
</P>
<P>
He argued that the reason why inflation rose to unprecedented
levels in 1993, immediately after last general elections in 1992,
is because there was capital flight and heavy injection of new
money into the economy from the printing press.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, CBK sources confirmed that the money market was
at this time round expected to benefit from foreign exchange
coming in to support political parties in the country during the
campaigning period.
</P>
<P>
The increased foreign exchange inflows have boosted the local
currency which was recently under pressure but has seen the
reversal of the depreciation trend, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Shilling dropped to 70 Shillings to the U.S. Dollar
in August when the International Monetary Fund (IMF) suspended
the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility funds to the country.
</P>
<P>
At present, the exchange rate is stabilized at some 63
Shillings to the Dollar due to the increased foreign exchange
inflows.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the enactment of the CBK Act this year has
given the monetary authority more control over monetary
management of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Under the Act, the CBK governor is able to enforce measures to
stabilize the economy without fear of a backlash from external
forces.
</P>
<P>
According to Amos Wako, attorney-general, the Act gives the
CBK "more independence in controlling money supply which is the
main source of inflationary pressure".
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the Act provides that government borrowing
from the CBK is restricted to five percent of the ordinary
revenue in the government's audited accounts.
</P>
<P>
This limit seals a loophole which in the past gave the
government access to funds held at the CBK.
</P>
<P>
Observers said fears of an upsurge in inflation in the
countdown to the coming general elections are giving way to
optimism because of strict money supply control and the sealing
of loopholes by the CBK. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
