<HEADLINE> Russia, Georgia Set Up Fuel Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Georgia have
established cooperation in the sphere of fuel and energy. This was
announced by Russian Deputy Prime Minister Valery Serov and
Georgian State Minister Miko Lekishvili at a joint press
conference on Tuesday in Tbilisi, Georgia.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax, among several Russian-Gerogian
accords signed today one agreement was signed between Russia's
Lukoil company and the Georgian Fuel and Energy Ministry. Another
accord provides for establishing a joint venture in transporting
and using natural gas.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Russia's Gazprom company are to finalize the
accord in late December in Tbilisi, Serov said. The issue of
Georgia's arrears for electric energy and natural gas supplies was
also resolved, according to him.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the pumping Russian natural gas to Turkey, Serov
said a pipeline will be built via Georgian and Armenian territory
carrying up to nine billion cubic meters of gas annually. another
project under consideration envisages constructing a pipeline
across the bottom of the Black Sea, Serov said.
</P>
<P>
As for military and technological ties, Serov said an accord
had been reached on leasing land and on Russia's responsibility
for the attendant environmental consequences.
</P>
<P>
A solution was found to the recent conflict in Daryal Canyon
after complicated negotiations. Serov said "commissions charged
with border and delimitation issues will start work immediately.
During this time, Georgian and Russian border guards will jointly
control the section."
</P>
<P>
Gerogian leadership is satisfied by the latest talks with the
Russian side and will continue its efforts towards attaining
strategic partnership with Russia, the Georgian minister said.
</P>
</TEXT>
