<HEADLINE> Zambia Urges Industrialized Nations to Assist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambia today urged
industrialized nations to assist developing ones in the latter's
efforts to alleviate poverty and address global climate changes.
</P>
<P>
William Harrington, Zambian Minister of Youth, Sports and
Child Development, made the appeal at the third conference of the
United Nations Framework Convention on Climate held in Tokyo,
Japan, according to the Zambia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said that the current climate changes are posing a threat
to people globally, hence the need for concerted efforts from all
countries.
</P>
<P>
Zambia considers the issue of climate change seriously as
demonstrated by the development and implementation of various
policies such as the national conservation strategy, national
environmental action plan, forest, energy, and agriculture
policies and the water master plan, said Harrington, who was
transferred to his new post from the ministry of environment and
natural resources in a sweeping cabinet reshuffle one week ago.
</P>
<P>
The former environment minister noted that for the developing
countries to achieve their goals, industrialized countries should
provide technological support accompanied by research and
development, capacity building and strengthening of institutions.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the need to involve people in climate change
debate and decision making through public awareness program.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 participants from governments, non-government
organizations and business community are attending the 10-day
conference, which will end on Wednesday. 
</P>
