<HEADLINE> Canada's Anti-tobacco Law Won't Ease, Minister Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Health Minister Allan
Rock has vowed that the government will not further weaken
anti-tobacco legislation in face of "blackmail" from cigarette
makers.
</P>
<P>
The government will only, as promised, amend the law to exempt
auto races from tough new sponsorship rules, he was quoted as
saying by reports today.
</P>
<P>
The minister was reacting to an announcement by Imperial
Tobacco that it will withdraw financial support by October from
cultural and sports events in Canada.
</P>
<P>
"We shall act when we are ready and we shall not influence, nor
shall we be intimidated by these pressure tactics from the tobacco
companies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under legislation to take effect next October, tobacco
advertizing for cultural and sports events is restricted to the
bottom 10 percent of an ad.
</P>
<P>
It also ban ads from broadcast outlets, billboards, street
kiosks, bus panels and store displays. Print ads are allowed only
in adult publications.
</P>
<P>
However, the exemptions would allow tobacco logos or
brand-names on cars and drivers' uniforms.
</P>
<P>
Health groups criticized the government for the exemptions,
saying it has already caved in as result of tobacco industry
pressures. The exemptions for car races will just make matters
worse, they said, while urging the government to stand up for
Canada's youths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
