<HEADLINE> Jordan, U.S. Plan Joint War Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and the United States
have hammered out a plan for joint military exercises next year,
Jordan's official news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
The plan was formally completed during separate meetings
between King Hussein and Crown Prince Hassan today and Monday and
a visiting U.S. military delegation, headed by General Anthony
Zinni, commander-in-chief of the U.S. Central Command.
</P>
<P>
Details of the plan will be guarded as military secrets,
Petra said.
</P>
<P>
Both meetings focused on bilateral military and economic
cooperation, especially in activating U.S. military assistance to
the Jordanian armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Zinni arrived here Sunday for a five-day visit ahead of the
delivery of 16 U.S.-made F-16 jet fighters, which are worth 200
million U.S. dollars. The fighters are expected in Jordan on
December 17.
</P>
<P>
The jet fighters will come as part of a 300 million dollars
military aid that the U.S. government promised to Jordan after the
kingdom signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994. Last December,
Jordan received 100 million dollars worth of military equipment
as the first part of the aid.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian and U.S. armed forces conducted annual military
exercises in recent years. This year's joint military drill was
held in May and June. 
