<HEADLINE> Inter-Party Talks Start in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's long-awaited
inter-party talks, which aim at solving the country's political
differences, started today with the participation of 29 political
parties.
</P>
<P>
The meeting which was held in the capital elected Micheal
Sata, Minister Without Portfolio, and Mainza Chona,
representative from the main opposition United National
Independence Party (UNIP), as co-chairman for the talks.
</P>
<P>
A five-member committee was also appointed to keep record and
consolidate deliberation of the meetings.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from both the ruling Movement for Multi-Party
Democracy (MMD) and the opposition parties showed seriousness and
the meeting carried on in a peaceful atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Sata was quoted by Zambia News Agency as saying that the
inter-party talks will be "successful".
</P>
<P>
Well begun is half done. However, it is still early to say
that the inter-party dialogue which resulted from substantial
external and internal pressures, will succeed in removing the
political differences since the ruling MMD cannot easily make a
concession in terms of electoral matters.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has been plagued with political disputes between the
ruling party and the Opposition since the general elections held
last year, which disciplined the presidential hopeful Kenneth
Kaunda, former president and UNIP leader by prohibiting foreign
nationals and those with foreign parentage from contesting the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties led by UNIP thereafter called for new
elections and revision of the constitution's provisions on
candidate qualifications and electoral process.
</P>
<P>
Under Zambia's new constitution which came into force just
before the country's second democratic elections held in 1996,
the president's tenure of office is limited to five year terms
twice.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Kaunda, who ruled Zambia for 27 years and has
foreign parentage--both of his parents are Malawian nationals,
could not run for the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
