<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1st Batch of Nigerian Troops to Return from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The first batch of Nigerian
soldiers is scheduled to return home next week from Liberia under
a phased pullout plan after a seven-year peace-keeping operation,
the military said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The ships have left Greenville for Monrovia and by today they
should finish loading and head for Lagos on the trip which takes
five to six days," said Colonel Ggodwin Ugbo, acting director of
defense information.
</P>
<P>
The military authorities are planning a reception for the
first 1,200 soldiers according to the tradition of the military,
the defense spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The phased pullout program was announced by ECOMOG force
commander Major-General Victor Malu earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG troops were first sent to Liberia in August 1990 to
help stop the conflict started in December 1989 by former warlord
Charles Taylor, who became president of the country after winning
the election in July this year.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has some 6,000 troops in ECOMOG, currently estimated
at 11,000-strong from 10 of the 16 countries that make up the
economic community of west African states (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
According to a peace agreement signed in Abuja last year, all
ECOMOG soldiers will leave Liberia before the end of February
next year.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord also asks ECOMOG to help restructure and
train Liberia's post-war army.
</P>
<P>
But Taylor said last month that his government intended to do
the job by itself, warning that the government would expel anyone
in the high command of ECOMOG that attempted to challenge or
share the constitutional power of the president.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent move to solve the problem, Taylor paid a
two-day visit to Nigeria last week. But the result of the visit
has not been made public.
</P>
<P>
As to whether ECOMOG will be involved in the restructuring and
training of the Liberian army, Ugbo said, it is up to the ECOWAS
authority to decide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
