<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Firm to Produce Artificial Heart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- An Ottawa-based company will
begin manufacturing its innovative artificial heart next month,
said reports today.
</P>
<P>
The device nicknamed Heartsaver is an implant developed by
scientists at the Ottawa Heart Institute, which is cooperating
with World Heart Corp.
</P>
<P>
It is superior to other ventricular assist devices (VAD)
because of its smallness and technical breakthroughs that allow it
to be powered and monitored by a device through the skin.
</P>
<P>
Patients using the device, which is expected to cost 50,000
Canadian dollars (35,000 US dollars), can live a normal life, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Animal trials of the device are slated to run through 1998, and
human use of the world's first fully implantable artificial heart
is expected in the following year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Worried at Conflicts in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
expressed its worry over the political conflicts and violence
resurfacing in Africa, the Zambia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
It quoted EU president for the Africa group and Luxemburg
Foreign Minister Fernand Kartheise as saying here Monday that
such occurrences are contributing to donor fatigue and loss of
confidence in the democratization process in many African
countries.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session of the EU-SADC (the Southern African
Development Community) joint committee of senior officials, he
said the results of the successful development cooperation with
donors in some countries have been completely destroyed by the
outbreak of violence.
</P>
<P>
"Public opinion and media find it increasingly hard to
understand that we devote our taxpayers' money to help countries
whose leaders are not capable of preserving peace or solving
their political problems without resorting to force," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said while EU remains confident with the democratic
principles taking root in Africa, the union is concerned with
armed conflicts, especially trans-border military activities that
have taken place without the mandate of competent international
bodies.
</P>
<P>
Kartheise said military solutions, from experience, do not
offer any solution to the root causes to conflicts among and
within nations.
</P>
<P>
He urged SADC organs on political, defense and security to
seriously address issues of conflict prevention and resolution
and management of crises.
</P>
<P>
Your success in promoting peace, stability, human rights and
democracy in Southern Africa will also be instrumental in
promoting the positive image of Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
The president expressed hope that despite the problems Africa
still remains a continent of hope with enormous human and
economic resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
