<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief: World Disappointed With Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan said here Tuesday that the world is disappointed with the
deadlock of the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He termed the Mideast peace situation as a common concern of
the United Nations and the Organization of Islamic Conference
(OIC).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the eighth OIC summit, Annan
said the international community "cannot but view with deep dismay
the continuing stalemate in the Israeli-Palestinian peace
negotiations."
</P>
<P>
He said it is essential that the terms of the Oslo peace
accords are respected to move forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief arrived here Monday to attend the Islamic
summit and pay his first visit to Iran.
</P>
<P>
He told delegates that the OIC has a critical role to play in
world peace and progress.
</P>
<P>
"Through you, the world understands the desires and demands of
over one-fifth of the world's population, from all continents," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He advocated partnership between the OIC and the U.N. in
peacemaking efforts in areas like Afghanistan, Somalia and
Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the U.N. enjoys the support of the OIC, together
with the Organization of African Unity and the Arab League, from
the early stages of crisis in Somalia, where he said the common
aim is a broad-based political solution.
</P>
<P>
On recent final peace accords for Tajikistan, he said that the
responsibility for various parties concerned is to establish and
consolidate stability to move toward a durable peace.
</P>
<P>
He said Afghanistan has proved elusive, despite painstaking
and persistent efforts by the OIC and the U.N., and a lasting
peace seems a distant prospect because "Afghan leaders refuse to
rise above their narrow factional interests."
</P>
<P>
He blamed external support for the continuing civil war,
growing human sufferings and worsening situations in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He said that the world cannot forget the horrifying atrocities
inflicted upon the people of Bosnia, the Muslims in particular.
</P>
<P>
"It is the duty of the international community to ensure that
those responsible for such genocidal policies are brought to
justice," he added.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he sees the OIC and the U.N. as "natural partners
in meeting the challenges of the new era and promoting peace and
prosperity throughout the world."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
