<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 22 African Countries Sign Declaration on Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of 22
African states today signed a declaration in South Africa
committing them to an integrated approach, including
international partnerships, to managing urban water resources.
</P>
<P>
The declaration was drawn up at a three-day conference on
water supply and sanitation in Somerset West, a city about 50
kilometers east of Cape Town, South African Press Association
reported.
</P>
<P>
Delegates were told that providing adequate water for human,
industrial and commercial use was one of the biggest challenges
facing governments and local authorities around the world.
</P>
<P>
The document noted that there was a growing gap between
available resources and the rapidly rising costs of providing
services.
</P>
<P>
The signatories agreed to promote partnerships between
countries and between all actors within countries to harness
resources.
</P>
<P>
They would promote innovative funding mechanism and make
affordable credit available to enable "the poorest of the poor"
to meet their own water and sanitation needs.
</P>
<P>
They would attempt to mobilize international financial
resources on equitable and affordable terms. The delegates also
endorsed an action program containing guidelines on rural
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
