<HEADLINE> Jordan Condemns Iraqi Execution of 4 Jordanians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian government today
issued an official statement to condemn the execution of four
Jordanians in Iraq Monday on charge of smuggling car spare parts,
Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
The execution took place despite Jordanian efforts at the
highest level to enlist information about the nature of the charge
against the four young men, the radio quoted the statement as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The statement described the execution as an "unjust" decision
to the four Jordanians.
</P>
<P>
Even if the charges proved to be true, the statement said, the
four Jordanians could only be punished with fines or prison terms.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government released the statement after its
cabinet decided to dispatch a medical team to Baghdad upon the
request of Iraq's health minister for humanitarian purposes,
according to the radio.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian-Iraqi relations suffered a setback after the 1990-91
Gulf Crisis. However, in recent years, the relations have been
picking up as Iraq provides the kingdom with more oil and keeps
increasing the volume of imports from Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Both sides are now discussing the increase of the Iraqi oil
supply for the kingdom in 1998. 
</P>
