<HEADLINE> European Shares Mixed, London's Rally Dies out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
ended mixed Tuesday, with London and Frankfurt all in the negative
grounds while Paris finishing firmer.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index closed lower for the first time in
four sessions, down 10.3 points at 5,177.1, as a report of weak
consumer spending hit retail stocks and Wall Street drifted lower.
</P>
<P>
The index had risen 217 points in the past three sessions.
</P>
<P>
But bid speculation kept the banking sector buoyant, with
Barclays up 4.2 percent on talk of a banking mega-merger.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt also ended at lower level on
profit-taking and consolidation after Monday's gains.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that a lack of domestic corporate news gave the
market little upward impetus as the DAX-30 index fell by 38.45
points at 4,184.91 by the end of the session.
</P>
<P>
However, the CAC-40 index in Paris closed 26.93 points higher
at 2,959.40.
</P>
<P>
A rally in banking shares in the wake of the Swiss UBS-SBC deal
boosted the market. 
</P>
