<HEADLINE> Cohen: Inspection Dispute Must Be Resolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said today that there should be ways to settle the
dispute between Iraq and the United States over weapons
inspections.
</P>
<P>
"It can't go on indefinitely without being resolved," Cohen
said at a joint news conference with South Korean Defense Minister
Kim Dong-jin.
</P>
<P>
Cohen postponed his six-day trip to the Middle East, scheduled
to begin Saturday, because of what the Pentagon said was the
continuing tension in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
A crisis over U.N. weapons inspections has been temporarily
defused since Iraqi President Saddam Hussein allowed U.N. weapons
inspectors, including several Americans, back to Baghdad to resume
their work.
</P>
<P>
But the United States still keeps a major air and naval force
in the Gulf region, claiming that the dispute remains as Baghdad
has refused the U.S. demand to search weapons of mass destruction
in Iraq's presidential areas, which the Iraqi government said are
off limits to inspections on the ground of sovereignty and
dignity.
</P>
<P>
Cohen acknowledged the tensions in the Gulf "has been eased,"
but he said, "They could intensify in the future in the event that
we don't see a resolution on that."
</P>
<P>
Cohen explained his decision to delay his Middle East trip was
made because of two issues that should be dealt with in the coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the continuing tension in the Gulf region, on which
Cohen has to be on alert as a defense secretary, he has to discuss
with President Bill Clinton and prepare for decisions on any new
NATO-led military force in Bosnia next June and on whether U.S.
troops might join such a force.
</P>
<P>
The postponement of the Middle East trip was "a decision on my
part in view of the fact that we have two major issues to deal
with in the coming weeks," he said. "I decided it would be prudent
for me to be in Washington next week when the president is here."
</P>
<P>
But he said he was "not being held hostage." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
