<HEADLINE> China Commodities Fair Opens in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The first ever large-scale
China Commodities Fair opened here today to further promote the
economic and trade cooperation between China and India.
</P>
<P>
The five-day fair was part of substantial follow-up actions
taken by the Chinese side to strengthen bilateral trade relations
after President Jiang Zemin's successful visit to India last year.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the inaugurating ceremony here today, Li Guohua,
vice minister of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation of the People's Republic of China, said that there
exists strong complementarity in Sino-Indian economic and trade
relations.
</P>
<P>
Further development of bilateral economic and trade cooperation
is not only in the common interests of two peoples but also
conducive to the stability and development in the region, she
said.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 leading Chinese enterprises from across the
country took part in the fair, the first of its kind that the
Chinese government has ever held in India over the decades.
</P>
<P>
With an exhibition area of over 2,000 square meters and over
100 standard booths, the fair will be a showcase of Chinese
products in such categories of machinery, hardware, minerals and
metals, medicines, textiles, and arts and crafts.
</P>
<P>
India is the leading trade partner of China in South Asia. In
1996, the bilateral trade volume between the two countries
amounted to a record high of 1.407 billion U.S. dollars, which was
20.9 percent higher than the previous year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
