<HEADLINE> German Court Demands FDP to Return Election Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- A court in Cologne ordered on
Wednesday a junior partner in the ruling coalition to return some
10.5 million marks (5.8 million U.S. dollars) in election funds.
</P>
<P>
The Free Democratic Party (FDP) was not entitled to get the
funds for this year from the state coffers, said a court ruling.
</P>
<P>
However, parliamentary president Rita Suessmuth said the FDP
could receive the funds for 1996 despite its failure to file
necessary applications before the deadline of September 30, 1996.
</P>
<P>
As decided by the court, Suessmuth, of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
Christian Democratic Union (CDU), could either ask the FDP to
return the money or deduct the sum from future payments to it.
</P>
<P>
Paying back the money is believed to plunge the FDP into a
financial predicament, which has only 6 million marks (2.86
million dollars) now on its book. 
</P>
</TEXT>
