<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small &AMP; Medium-Sized Firms in HK Encouraged to Seek </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 10 (Xinhua) -- A senior Hong Kong official
said here today that the government would strive to create a
business-friendly environment for small and medium-sized
enterprises (SMEs), which account for 98 percent of the total
industrial and commercial firms in the city.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar titled "Small and Medium-sized Enterprises
Day", Anson Chan, Secretary for Administration, said: "To promote
the development of small and medium-sized enterprises, the most
important macroeconomic element is to create free and
level-playing environment with minimum government intervention."
</P>
<P>
She stressed: "Business decisions should be made by
entrepreneurs themselves."
</P>
<P>
According to Chan, a clear and simple taxation system with low
tax rate, a level-playing field for local and overseas business,
an open, fair and just judicial system, and a clean, efficient
contingent of civil servants are what the government will do for
SMEs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government will also provide a support for
SMEs in marketing, financing, technology application, and human
resources management.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has 280,000 SMEs, dominating over the manufacturing
and services sectors. These enterprises employ 60 percent of the
working population in the city.
</P>
<P>
Today's seminar provided a forum for entrepreneurs and
officials to share their views on the opportunities, difficulties
and challenges faced with the SMEs.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey conducted by the Chinese Manufacturers'
Association of Hong Kong shows that 90 percent of its members have
invested in the inland areas of China. About 43 percent said that
they would increase their investment in inland provinces in the
next three years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
