<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea Suspends Operation of Five More Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government
decided Wednesday to suspend the operation of five more merchant
banks, so as to help stabilize the financial market.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Finance and Economy Lim Cahng-yuel unveiled the
stepped up measure at a press conference, thus bringing the number
of merchant banks under temporary lock-up to a total 14.
</P>
<P>
The five banks are Taehab, Choong'ang, Hanwha, Shinhan and Nara.
</P>
<P>
The stringent measure, effective from December 11 through
January 31, 1998, is Seoul's fresh move, after closing down nine
others on December 2, to ease jitters in the financial market.
</P>
<P>
Under a directive by the ministry, the ailing banks have to
submit their self-rescue programs by the end of the year. If they
fail to put their management in order by March 1998, their
business license will be suspended.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's financial crisis was caused by the failure of a
group of corporates and the bad loans of financial institutions.
The loans, estimated at over 30 billion U.S. dollars, has sent the
Korean currency won plunging to new low against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Seoul appealed to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on
November 21 to help the world's 11th largest economy out.
</P>
<P>
After a week of bargaining with the IMF, South Korea, with a
staggering debt of 110 billion dollars, accepted 57 billion dollar
loans with strict terms from the financial institution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
