<HEADLINE> Malaysian King Urges People to Face Hardship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Supreme Head of
State Tuanku Ja'afar tonight urged Malaysians to be prepared to
face hardship caused by currency manipulation without hoping for
help from anyone but from themselves.
</P>
<P>
Opening the International Al-Quran Reading Competition 1997
here tonight, the king said that the country's economy affected by
the currency manipulation was a test for the people.
</P>
<P>
"I believe Muslims in this country have the will power to face
the economic problem with determination," he said.
</P>
<P>
The king said the people should make sacrifices to ensure the
success of measures taken by the government to improve the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
The austerity drive, increasing productivity, the use of more
locally-made products, reducing imports and increasing exports
were among the strategies introduced by the government which
should get the support from the people to help draw the country
out of its economic woes, the king said.
</P>
<P>
Reminding Muslims of their responsibilities to defend the
sanctity and integrity of Muslims worldwide, Tuanku Ja'afar said
"We do not want Muslims in the world to be the target of insults
and hatred."
</P>
<P>
He said that Muslims should learn from the tragic events which
happened and are still happening to Muslims and should endeavor to
rectify the situation.
</P>
<P>
Muslims in Malaysia should learn from the incidents involving
Muslims elsewhere and should not be beguiled by a life of comfort
and prosperity, he said, adding that they should also be prepared
to face all eventualities and through determination they could
avoid hardship and sufferings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
