<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disapproval Rate for Hashimoto Cabinet Rises to 52.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Public disapproval rate for
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's cabinet has increased
to 52.1 percent from the previous high of 49.0 percent in October.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time, said the Kyodo News while releasing its
survey findings Wednesday, the disapproval for the cabinet topped
the 50 percent mark since Hashimoto took office in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
The increased public discontent was attributed to the economic
slump and uncertainty about the financial systems following the
collapses of a series of Japanese financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The opinion poll, conducted through interviews during the last
weekend, covered 3,000 voters randomly selected nationwide, of
whom 2,023 responded. An error margin of 3 percent was expected.
</P>
<P>
On reasons of disapproval, 26.5 percent of pollees cited
disappointment with the government's economic policy, followed by
Hashimoto's perceived lack of leadership at 24.2 percent and
discontent about his administrative refrom drive at 12.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the cabinet's support rate is at the all-time low of
42.0 percent, down 1.6 percentage points from the previous poll in
October and below the previous low of 43.4 percent in March last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
