<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Snowfall Disrupts Islamic Summit in Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Tehran's first snowfall this
winter caused electricity failures and forced Islamic leaders to
adjourn their summit this morning.
</P>
<P>
A total blackout descended on the summit center after Pakistani
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif delivered a speech at the beginning of
today's closing session.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami, who chaired the meeting,
had to call a "temporary recess." The power failures lasted about
seven minutes.
</P>
<P>
However, a leak on the roof of the newly-built 30-meter-high
summit hall further suspended the meeting until 3 o'clock this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency IRNA said in a dispatch that the
power problems "presented an opportunity for the Muslim leaders,
prime ministers and crown princes to enjoy the magnificent sight
of the snowfall."
</P>
<P>
Delegates gathered in front of the glass windows of the hall to
watch the swirling fall of the feathery snowflakes. "The nature's
blessing is particularly interesting for the African leaders
present in the summit," IRNA said.
</P>
<P>
Summit spokesman and Iran's Deputy Foreign Minister Mohammad
Javad Zarif explained at a news briefing that the suspension of
the meeting was to prevent the recurrence of the "small problem"
inside the hall.
</P>
<P>
The summit hall, which can hold 1,500 people in its main
conference room, took six months to complete for the ongoing
Islamic summit.
</P>
<P>
The snowfall stopped, and sunshine enlivened soon after noon.
</P>
</TEXT>
