<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flu Virus Confirmed With Origin in Birds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Medical specialists
confirmed that the H5N1 virus, which has caused two fatalities in
Hong Kong by triggering influenza A, was originated in birds.
</P>
<P>
A special working group is continuing to track down the H5N1
virus, recently found only in poultry, to find out how it is
transmitted to humans, the Department of Health said here today.
</P>
<P>
The virus have infected four people in Hong Kong, and led to
the death of two. Dr. K H Mak, a consultant of the Department of
Health said here today at a press briefing: "In fact, in the four
cases of H5N1, only one had history of exposure to poultry. The
other three did not have known history of contact with poultry
during the incubation period of influenza."
</P>
<P>
He advised people to take personal hygienic measures such as
washing hands with soap after handling poultry, but denied that
eating poultry could pose a risk.
</P>
<P>
Dr.Mak warned the public of initial signs of H5N1 influenza A,
such as fever, cough, sore throat and running nose. He added that
the best protection is to maintain body immunity by having a
balanced diet, adequate rest and exercise, and good
ventilation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
