<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- With investor confidence again starting to erode, the South
Korean government called on the U.S. and Japan Tuesday to quickly
provide the money that they had pledged only as a lost resort.
</P>
<P>
-- As a deadline neared in Kyoto, Japan, negotiators from more
than 150 nations inched toward a pact on cutting greenhouse gases
emission.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Iran opened an Islamic summit meeting Tuesday with the aim
of promoting unity among the world's one billion Muslims.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright began a
seven-nation tour of Africa Tuesday by acknowledging that the
Clinton administration and its allies mishandled the 1994 Rwandan
crisis -- a recognition that aides said is central to a new U.S.
approach to Africa that she is presenting on this trip.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The International Monetary Fund is moving rapidly to create
a quick, big-money lending program designed to bail out emerging
market countries that have lost confidence of foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
-- Talks on a Korean peace began for the first time since a
1953 armistice ended the Korean War, but swift progress isn't
likely, as the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, South Korea,
China and the U.S. sit down in Geneva. 
