<HEADLINE> China Promotes Dissemination of Science in Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- China plans to introduce a
1998 program to disseminate scientific information to promote
economic development and improve morale in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
According to a joint circular issued by the Propaganda
Department of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee and
the Central Committee of the Chinese Communist Youth League, some
5,000 libraries will be established early next year, with at least
one facility in every county.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey indicates that the lack of scientific
information in the countryside has limited both increases in grain
output and development of a commercialized rural economy.
</P>
<P>
The circular calls on Youth League members, entrepreneurs and
young scientists to donate science books and video tapes to the
libraries, and for the establishment of clubs catering to readers.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 volunteer teams will be organized to provide
services and teach farmers how to properly use science and
technology, according to the circular.
</P>
<P>
The libraries will offer science classes to over 10 million
young farmers, with additional classes to be offered by Party
schools, night schools and vocational high schools.
</P>
<P>
Related work is considered to be an important aspect of efforts
to implement policies of the 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China regarding improving the cultural,
scientific and sanitary conditions in rural areas, and
consolidating grass roots Youth League organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
