<HEADLINE> Atmosphere Improved for Iran-Arab Ties: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said here today that the atmosphere has improved for
better relations between Iran and Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Replying questions from Xinhua on the sidelines of the ongoing
Islamic summit, Moussa said he has discussed with Iranian
officials about the general atmosphere for relations between Iran
and Egypt, and Arab states in general.
</P>
<P>
"What we have seen in general has been improved and will have
influence on the relations between Iran and Saudi Arabia, Egypt
and other countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But we are still working to further improve our relations"
which should be "as good as we aspire," he added.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and Arab states cooled down after
Iran's Islamic Revolution in 1979. However, Tehran has launched a
series of initiatives to reach out for the Arab world in a bid to
break isolation enforced by Western countries led by the United
States.
</P>
<P>
After Mohammad Khatami won the presidential elections in May,
Iran repeatedly announced its readiness to develop friendly
relations with Arab neighbors, particularly the Gulf states and
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the summit of the Organization of the
Islamic Conference (OIC) which opened here Tuesday would be fully
tapped by Iran to remove obstacles in the way for rapprochement
with Arab states. 
</P>
