<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Economy Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- A healthy performance by the
tourism and services sectors in Cyprus has help the country's
economy maintain a steady pace of recovery since May this year,
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou was quoted as
saying that the Cyprus economy is now expected to end the year
with a 2.5 percent growth in gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
"The revival of the economy which started in May this year is
steadily continuing with its main driving force being tourism,
offshore and other services sectors," the minister told local
press Tuesday after a meeting with senior officials devoted to
reviewing the island's economy.
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou said the GDP grew at only one percent in the
first six months of the year, but it picked up pace in the second
half to register an impressive 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of tourists rose 8 percent year-on-year
for the May-October period of this year, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the GDP registered a modest growth of 1.9 percent as a
result of a severe drought and tension on the Green Line, which
undermined investors' confidence and hit tourism. Tourism, one of
the island's main sources of income, accounts for nearly 20
percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
The previous year, 1995, witnessed GDP growth of 6 percent
with an all-time record of 2.2 million tourists visiting the
island.
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou gave a good prospect for 1998, saying that the
growth rate is expected to reach 4.5 percent and an improvement
is foreseen for other macro-economic indicators of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou's prediction was agreed by Governor of the
Central Bank, Afxentis Afxentiou, who said during the second
half of this year there has been a significant improvement in
the economy which is set to continue in 1998 if there are no
adverse developments.
</P>
<P>
With regard to other indicators, Christodoulou said
unemployment was forecast to reach 3.3 percent and inflation 3.5
percent in 1997 in comparison with 3.1 percent and 3 percent in
1996 respectively.
</P>
<P>
He listed what he called "temporary" factors for the rise in
inflation, together with a lingering drought which had an impact
on prices of farm products.
</P>
<P>
The devaluation of the Cyprus pound against the U.S. dollar
and higher oil prices on world markets last year and in early
1997 contributed to a hike in electricity costs.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the island's foreign exchange
reserves are set to grow to 2.8 billion Cyprus pounds (about 5.6
billion U.S. dollars) in 1997, enough for 14 months of imports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
