<HEADLINE> China Lifts Fourth World Record at World Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHIANG MAI, Thailand, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Chen Yanqing set
China's fourth world record in five days at the world weighlifting
championships here on Wednsday.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old from Jiangsu Province jerked 131 kilograms in
the women's 64kg class for the gold, breaking the previous mark of
130.5kg set by compatriot Shi Lihua at the junior world
championships in Finland in August.
</P>
<P>
Chen also bagged another gold with a total of 230kg but came
second in the snatch with 100.0kg.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jui-lien of Chinese Taipei won the snatch with
102.5kg. She also took two silvers with 122.5kg in the jerk and
225.0kg for the total.
</P>
<P>
India's Laxmi Neelamsetti won the snatch and total bronzes with
100.0kg and 217.5kg respectively.
</P>
<P>
The other bronze went to China's Lu Yun, who jerked 122.5kg.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 76kg category, Bulgarian Yoto Yotov lifted a total
of 367.5kg for the gold, with compatriot Georgi Gardev at second
with 365kg and Poland's Andrzej Kozlowski at third with 362.5kg.
</P>
<P>
Yotov also captured the jerk gold at 202.5kg, Gardev denied him
a sweep by winning the snatch with 167.5kg. Yotov took the bronze
with 165kg following another Polish Waldemar Kosinski, who also
snatched 165kg but won the silver with a bodyweight advantage.
</P>
<P>
Kosinski also won the bronze after jerking 197.5kg, behind
compatriot Kozlowsi with 200kg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
