<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Australian FMs Hold Talks in Beijing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen here today expressed full
satisfaction with the marked progress of Sino-Australian ties over
the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with visiting Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer, Qian warmly welcomed Downer, who is visiting
China during celebrations marking the 25th anniversary of the
establishment of diplomatic ties between the two nations. He said
that Downer's visit is yet another moment deserving of celebration.
</P>
<P>
Qian noted the sound progress in bilateral relations over the
past 25 years, and pointed to frequent high-level contacts and
exchange of visits.
</P>
<P>
Various government departments from the two countries have
established regular consultation mechanisms and engaged in
extensive negotiations and cooperation related to regional and
international affairs, Qian said, adding that economic and trade
relations have witnessed continuous rapid development, with
increasing mutual investment.
</P>
<P>
He said that positive results have been recorded in cultural,
scientific, technological, military, educational and public health
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the Australian government has adopted a positive
attitude towards the issue of China's entry into the World Trade
Organization (WTO). He also expressed appreciation for Australia's
persistent adherence to the `One China' policy concerning the
Taiwan issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Australian FMs Hold Talks in Beijing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Downer expressed great pleasure at having the opportunity to
attend celebrations marking the 25th anniversary of the
establishment of diplomatic relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that bilateral relations have developed in all aspects
over the past 25 years, with the volume of bilateral trade growing
substantially during the period. He also stressed Australia's
satisfaction with the current status of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Downer said the fact that the two countries have not only
maintained, but have also increased high-level contacts and
exchange of visits, has greatly promoted the development of
bilateral relations. He expressed the hope that even more Chinese
leaders will visit Australia in the future.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers agreed that long-term, stable and
mutually beneficial relations of cooperation between the two
countries will be in the long-term interests of the two peoples
and will at the same time be highly beneficial to ensuring peace,
stability and development in the Asia-Pacific Region. They agreed
that the two sides will continue to promote the Sino-Australian
relationship to a higher plateau.
</P>
<P>
Qian noted that China has agreed in principle to designate
Australia as an official tourist destination for Chinese
citizens. The two sides expect the decision to facilitate
personnel exchanges and play a positive role in strengthening
understanding and friendship between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also exchanged views on international
and regional issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Downer and his entourage arrived in Beijing on Tuesday for a
three-day visit to China. This is Downer's second visit to China
during his tenure as foreign minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
