<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Takes Measures to Encourage Commercialization of Research Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government has
taken a number of measures to encourage the staff of universities
to conduct applied research and promote commercialization of
technological research results, a government official said today.
</P>
<P>
The government, through the University Grants Committee,
encourages institutions of higher learning to conduct both basic
and applied research by providing funding and the necessary
infrastructure, said Joseph Wong, secretary for Education and
Manpower of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of
China.
</P>
<P>
In response to an inquiry by a member of the Provisional
Legislative Council, Wong said that funding for research projects
by the government has risen from 122 million HK dollars (15.64
million U.S. dollars) in 1991-92 to 423 million HK dollars (54.23
million U.S. dollars) in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
The government has established the Industrial Support Fund
(ISF) and the Applied Research Council (ARC) to provide dedicated
funding for applied research, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
The ISF supports projects that will enhance the development and
competitiveness of the manufacturing sector in Hong Kong while
the ARC supports private sector's technology ventures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
