<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The debate on 35-hour work week draft law presented by the
Minister of Employment and Solidarity Martine Aubry has entered a
crucial phase: the employers are on a war call, the trade unions are
divided while employees are prudent over whether the law will hurt
employment. In the Loire-Atlantique region in western France, the
local employers' association staged an insurrection against the
draft law at a gathering in Nante on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
-- The Senegalese capital of Dakar has been saved from an
expansion of AIDS over the past several years, due to its control
of the prostitution trade in the city by obliging the use of
condom by porstitutes, while the rate of local population attained
by AIDS virus in Abidjan has reached 10 percent over the past five
years, the highest in West Africa, because of its failure to
control the prostitution trade there, said experts at the
International Conference on AIDS in Africa being held in Abidjan
this week.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel was the prior target of the Iranian leaders and several
heads of state of the Muslim world on the first day of the eighth
summit of the Organization of Islamic Conference which began Tuesday
in Teheran. Iranian President Mohammad Khatami accused Israel of
being a "warlike, terrorist and racist" state, while Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad accused Israel of the being "the source of
all plots against the Arab or Islamic countries."
</P>
<P>
-- The European Court of Justice ruled on Tuesday that France
"missed its obligations" to ensure the free circulation of goods
suring the manifestations by French farmers in 1993 and 1994.
Spanish transporters and farmers who were the mainly victims of the
violence by French farmers, had sued France at the court. 
</P>
