<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Oks 250 Million Dollars loan for Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
announced a 250 million U.S. dollars loan to Pakistan in support
of the country's banking sector reform.
</P>
<P>
The loan will provide balance of payment assistance to the
government of Pakistan, which has already completed the first
phase of reforms aimed at stemming the flow of bad loans and
curtailing loss-making by banks, said a press release issued by
the World Bank office here today.
</P>
<P>
The Single Currency Loan (SCL) will be repayable in 20 years
including a 5-year grace period, and will be at the World Bank's
standard variable U.S. Dollar SCL interest rate, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government and the central bank began the reforms
early this year in an attempt to eliminate political interference
that had left the predominantly state-owned banking sector on the
verge of a crisis, the release said.
</P>
<P>
In the next phase of the program, emphasis will be placed on
assuring that the Nationalized Commercial Banks and Development
Finance Institutions are sold to private investors, it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
