<HEADLINE> Soeharto to Attend Informal ASEAN Summit in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
has decided to attend the informal ASEAN (Association of Southeast
Asian Nations) summit to be held in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia on
December 15-16, a senior official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The president will leave on the morning of December 15 and
return to Jakarta on December 16," Minister/State Secretary
Moerdiono said after meeting with the president at the latter's
residence in Jalan Cendana, Central Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, Soeharto, who is now taking a full 10-day
rest under the advice of medical experts, will also attend a
meeting between the ASEAN and China, South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto started to rest on December 6 after a 12-day overseas
visit to Namibia, South Africa, Canada and Saudi Arabia. On
Tuesday, rumors said the president was ill, prompting the
Indonesian rupiah to drop sharply by 11 percent in a single day to
4,600 against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
However, Moerdiono denied the rumors on Tuesday night, saying
that the president was in good health.
</P>
<P>
Moerdiono said the president will invite ASEAN leaders to
discuss the monetary crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the nine ASEAN member countries, Brunei, Indonesia,
Malaysia, Myanmar, Laos, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam, will also witness their foreign ministers to sign an
agreement on the setting up of the ASEAN Foundation and on
cooperation in services.
</P>
<P>
Following the informal ASEAN summit, the ASEAN leaders will
hold talks with United Nations Secretary General Koffi Annan, who
is expected to be in Malaysia at the invitation of Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohammad.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN leaders on December 16 will also meet with their
Chinese, South Korean and Japanese counterparts for bilateral
talks, an official of the ASEAN Secretariat said here today.
</P>
<P>
The official said although they have no special agenda for
these bilateral meetings, the leaders will discuss how to face the
21st century in East Asia and Southeast Asia, and how to respond
to international problems.  
</P>
</TEXT>
