<HEADLINE> Serb Leaders Quit Bosnia Conference in Bonn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia (FRY) and the Bosnian Serb republic walked out of an
international meeting on Bosnia here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The boycott, in protest against what they alleged as Western
intervention in the Kosovo issue, took place shortly before the
annual conference, the third of the kind, was due to end.
</P>
<P>
Leaving the event were FRY Foreign Ministry Director Dragomir
Vucicevic, Bosnian Serb President Biljana Plavsic and the Serb
member of Bosnia's collective presidency, Momcilo Krajisnik.
</P>
<P>
What prompted them to quit was the inclusion of Western demands
in the meeting's communique that Belgrade negotiate with ethnic
Albanians in its Kosovo region to defuse ethnic tensions there.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel called on the
FRY to start talks on the Kosovo issue, and vowed to do everything
possible to "extinguish the source of fire" there.
</P>
<P>
His remarks immediately invoked criticism from FRY
representatives, who threatened to boycott the meeting if the
Kosovo issue would be put on agenda.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade termed the Western demands as interference in its
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference was to review, by officials from 50
countries and 21 international organizations, the implementation
of the November 1995 Dayton peace accord for Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Among its results was an approval from Bosnian leaders of a
common passport and citizenship for Bosnia, a long-sought decision
which has yet to be approved by the Bosnian parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, they still refused to approve the introduction of a
common currency and common car license plate.
</P>
<P>
Western nations made their intention clear to use the Bonn
meeting as a venue for exerting increased pressure on the Bosnian
leadership for better compliance with the Dayton accord.
</P>
<P>
"The signal ... must be: Those who want reconciliation will
receive our help. Those who do not implement Dayton accord, who
seek to obstruct the recovery effort, will bear the consequences,"
Kinkel said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
