<HEADLINE> Flood-Hit Somalia to Get Aid from UNFAO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) will provide to Somalia flood-hit emergency aid
of seeds and farm implements worth 400,000 U.S. Dollars, said a
FAO report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
About 20,000 farm families in Gedo and Middle and Lower Juba,
southern Somalia, will receive help from FAO, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
The Rome-based FAO said it is to begin buying 2,000 packs of
assorted vegetable seeds this week and then airlift them to
Somalia. The body will also provide sesame and cow pea seeds and
small hand tools to the Horn of Africa country.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,500 Somalis died with another 230,000 displaced when
floods heavily hit southern Somalia because of abnormal
torrential rains in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
Estimated 60,000 hectares of crops and farmland there were
also destroyed by the floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
