<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals to Macao Drops 13.2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals dropped 13.2
percent in the first ten months of the year from the same period
last year, latest statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Macao Census and Statistics Department
show that the number of tourists arriving in Macao between January
and October added up to 5,912,776, down 13.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Although tourists from Taiwan, Portugal and France increased,
those from Macao's main sources of tourists, including Japan, Hong
Kong, China's inland areas and the Republic of Korea, all dropped
remarkably.
</P>
<P>
The number of travelers from Japan plummeted 38.1 percent from
the same period last year, and those from Australia, 19 percent,
those from Hong Kong, 16.9 percent and those from China's inland
areas, 10.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The decline of tourists was also seen at the Hong Kong-Macao
port terminal, which has remained quiet most of the time since
April. It recorded a nearly 20 percent drop in arrivals from Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Tourists coming from Hong Kong used to account for some 70
percent of all tourist arrivals, which reached 8.15 million last
year.
</P>
<P>
Macao tourism officials blamed "exaggerated reports" on Macao
security problems, the financial crisis in Southeast Asia and less
 tourist arrivals to Hong Kong for the decline. They vowed to
attract more tourists next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
