<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Toys Sell Well in U.S. Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Brisk sales in the United
States retail market have fueled Hong Kong's toy exports, which
are expected to grow by 10 percent this year, sources from the
Hong Kong Trade Development Council (TDC) said today.
</P>
<P>
Edmund Young, chairman of the TDC's Toy Advisory Committee,
said that the American retail market registered satisfactory
growth in the third quarter and sales were particularly strong
during the Thanksgiving period.
</P>
<P>
In the first three quarters of this year, Hong Kong's total
exports of toys, dolls and games added up to 66 billion HK dollars
(8.5 billion US dollars), up 8 percent over the same period last
year. Exports to the United States rose by 7 percent and accounted
for 48.2 percent of Hong Kong's total toy exports.
</P>
<P>
Toy exports to Southeast Asia could be affected since Hong Kong
products are relatively expensive for consumers in those
countries, where currencies were depreciated in recent financial
turmoil, according to Young.
</P>
<P>
The TDC will organize a large-scale toys and games fair in
January 1998, in an effort to promote Hong Kong's products to a
wider spectrum of markets. Young said that baby toys and sporting
goods were two main categories in Hong Kong's toy exports.
</P>
</TEXT>
