<HEADLINE> Zambia Trying to Improve Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Zambia needs to improve its
poor image to attract more foreign investment, Bwalga Ng'andu,
director of Zambia Investment Center (IC) said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing held at the State House, Ng'andu said that
Zambia shared a "poor" image with Africa as a whole, which
impedes the inflows of foreign direct investment into the
country.
</P>
<P>
When asked by Xinhua to specify Africa's negative image which
Zambia shares part of it, Ng'andu said that the image is
characterized by military coups, AIDS, lower productivity and
inefficiency.
</P>
<P>
He added that this image has weakened the investors'
confidence and leads to a conception by western countries that
the continent is a "small African village".
</P>
<P>
This is the obvious reason why the continent has so long been
ignored by potential investors, stressed the IC director.
</P>
<P>
However, Ng'andu pointed out that "business is not 100 percent
risk free", urging foreign investors to "come and have a look" in
order to have a better understanding of the country and its
people.
</P>
<P>
He added that Zambia needs to inform the world that things are
changing and the investment environment is improving since there
is no foreign exchange controls in the country and the country's
tariffs is the lowest in the sub-continent.
</P>
<P>
In the past several years, the inflows of foreign direct
investment into Zambia represents a growing tendency. In 1995,
according to Ng'andu, the country registered 56 million U.S.
Dollars of such investment while in 1996, the inflows reached 62
million Dollars, with an increase by about 10 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
