<HEADLINE> All hostages in Hijacked Russian Plane Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Russian security forces seized
a man who hijacked a passenger plane with about 140 people aboard
on Wednesday and all the hostages were released unharmed, airport
and security officials said.
</P>
<P>
The hijacker was arrested by anti-terrorist "Alfa" group when
he came out to negotiate at Moscow's Sheremetyevo airport, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The hijacker, a 59-year-old man, seized the Ilyushin-62
airliner earlier on Wednesday after it took off from the Far
Eastern city of Magadan en route to Moscow with about 140
passengers and crew on board.
</P>
<P>
The hijacker had demanded 10 million U.S. dollars in cash and
safe passage to Switzerland, officials said.
</P>
<P>
An airport spokeswoman said earlier that the hijacker had
surrendered but later reports made clear he had been seized by
commandos.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Zaitsev, head of Russia's Federal Aviation Service,
said the hiajacker had been "wired up" but it was not immediately
clear whether he had been carrying any real explosives.
</P>
<P>
The plane landed at about 11.30 a.m. local time (0830 GMT) at
Sheremetyevo airport. The hijackers released 48 hostages at 12:15
a.m. (0915 GMT). There were no foreign passengers on board the
plane.
</P>
<P>
The seized hijacker hinted earlier that there were three
hijackers, the Itar-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Boris Yeltsin's spokesman, Sergei
Yastrzhembsky, as saying the president was pleased by the peaceful
outcome to the hijacking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
