<HEADLINE> Lagos Computerize Criminal Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The judicial departments in
Lagos State will find it an easy job to ascertain the names and
profiles of those facing or awaiting trial with the ongoing
computerization of the state's criminal records.
</P>
<P>
The development will enhance the speedy trial of criminals,
said Fola Arthur-Worrey, Director of Public Prosecutions of the
Lagos State Ministry of Justice, quoted by the Guardian today.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 2,000 inmates awaiting trial in Lagos
prisons and 1,350 case files have been computerized, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, record-keeping is the basic tool in criminal
justice, henceforth undue delays in charging cases to court would
be considerably reduced.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has been accused by human rights groups both at home
and abroad of human rights abuse. One of the allegations is
keeping people in prison without trial.  
</P>
