<HEADLINE> Philippines Conducts Cloud Seeding against Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- A cloud seeding project of the
Department of Agriculture aimed at mitigating the effects of El
Nino has resulted in increased water inflow in Metro Manila
equivalent to 14-day consumption, a presidential press release
said today.
</P>
<P>
The release said Agriculture Secretary Salvador Escudero
reported to President Fidel Ramos on Tuesday that cloud seeding
activities conducted in Metro Manila and nearby areas had led to
heavy rains from December 5 to 8.
</P>
<P>
Escudero added that cloud-seeding aircraft will also be sent
this week to provinces in the central and southern parts of the
country to ease the drought there caused by El Nino.
</P>
<P>
However, witnesses said that a water rationing system is still
in effect in Metro Manila due to the sharp fall of water levels of
main reservoirs supplying water to the capital city.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has been taking measures to cushion
the effects of the El Nino phenomenon, including digging deep
wells, constructing water projects and water rationing as well as
cloud seeding.  
</P>
