<HEADLINE> Lebanese First On-line Mall Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese first on-line mall
opened its doors Wednesday with the launch of a website on the
Internet for shopping while surfing, Lebanese newspaper the
Beirut Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that net surfers in Lebanon and around the
world can now make purchases on the shopping mall created by the
Data Management, the country's largest Internet service company.
</P>
<P>
The payment procedure is done through a Klebox, a secure
virtual wallet which contains credit cards for expensive
purchases and change in the customer's own currency for small
purchases.
</P>
<P>
The Klebox service was developed by KLELine, a financial
service company based in France, which offers a set of secured
payment services on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"For the customer, this service is completely free of charge as
no fee transaction is debited. The merchant is the one paying the
whole cost," said Abdallah Hitti, general director of KLELine.
</P>
<P>
The Data Management spent 250,000 U.S. dollars and eight
months of constant work to set up the website.
</P>
<P>
In Lebanon with a population of about 3.5 million, personal
computers currently stand at about 80,000 and internet
subscribers an estimated 14,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
