<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Launch Two Major Railway Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government has
 decided to construct two railway lines to ease transport
pressures at a cost of at least 9 billion Hong Kong dollars (1.15
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The plan was unveiled by Nicholas Ng Wing-fui, secretary for
transport, after a meeting of the Executive Council on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new projects include a 10.3-kilometer railway line in New
Territories from Ma On Shan to Tai Wai and another line in Kowloon
from Hunghom terminus to an underground station at Tsim Sha Tsui.
</P>
<P>
They are scheduled for completion between 2003 and 2004.
</P>
<P>
The Ma On Shan Rail with a total cost of about 6.7 billion Hong
Kong dollars (859 million U.S. dollars) will provide a
high-capacity transport link for residents of New Territories.
</P>
<P>
"With a daily capacity of 279,000 passengers, the rail will
bring convenient transport to the 500,000 residents of the
northeast New Territories," Ng said.
</P>
<P>
Kowloon-Canton Railway Corporation will run both projects and
it will submit a detailed proposal on their development. 
</P>
