<HEADLINE> Soaring CD Import from Shanghai Customs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 10 (Xinhua) -- From January to November,
1.85 million CDs were imported through Shanghai Customs, 10.2
times more than the same period of last year, according to
statistics released by the customs office of this economic
powerhouse of China.
</P>
<P>
Government officials attributed the rise to the efforts taken
by the Shanghai Customs and other government offices in cracking
down on pirate products and smuggling, and maintaining sound
import and export order.
</P>
<P>
Most of the imported CDs here feature Chinese classical music
and dancing music with domestic copyright. Experts say the reason
behind is that Chinese CD makers lack the ability to produce
quality goods.
</P>
<P>
70 percent of the CDs coming through the Shanghai Customs are
imported from Japan. The rest are form Hong Kong, the United
States and Singapore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
