<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Swiss Envoy Bullish About Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The current situation in
Hong Kong is much better than what people expected five months
ago, said Rolf Bodenmuller, Switzerland's consul-general in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
"I had been always confident about the handover and the future
of Hong Kong," Bodenmuller said in an exclusive interview with
Xinhua in his office at Gloucester Tower.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, I feared some changes might take place," said
Bodenmuller, who assumed his current position in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
People feared interference from Beijing might affect the
operation of the Hong Kong government, soldiers of the People's
Liberation Army (PLA) might bring troubles to the peaceful life of
the Hong Kong citizens and cases of corruption might increase
after the handover, Bodenmuller said.
</P>
<P>
"But now I see no sign of interference from Beijing, the PLA
soldiers are out of sight of the people and a recent report of the
Independent Commission Against Corruption said that the cases of
corruption had decreased," the gray-haired Bodenmuller said.
</P>
<P>
Sitting comfortably in his chair and smoking a pipe,
Bodenmuller spoke highly of the efficient work of the ICAC after
the handover. "ICAC has been widely recognized for its excellent
contribution to the anti-corruption."
</P>
<P>
Looking out from the windows of his office, which is on the
37th floor, ships were sailing on the Victoria Harbor and cars
running in streets.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to the sea and the streets, Bodenmuller said: "Look,
everything is working the ways it worked before. I don't notice
any changes. Of course, the flags are different."
</P>
<P>
Bodenmuller, born and educated in Berne, joined the diplomatic
service in 1973 and has undertaken several foreign postings in
Copenhagen, East Berlin, Pretoria and Rome.
</P>
<P>
Last month was special for Bodenmuller and his colleagues. They
were busy organizing the month-long promotion entitled
"Switzerland Greets Hong Kong".
</P>
<P>
The objective of the activity was to make Switzerland and its
many-sided faces better known to the people of Hong Kong. They
showed the Hong Kong people Switzerland's business, tourism,
culture, gastronomy, arts and music.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss people and enterprises want to express their strong
confidence in the future of Hong Kong and their firm commitment to
enhance the excellent bilateral relationship between Switzerland
and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Bodenmuller described the activity as "very successful". "We
are very happy about the results. The press coverage was very good
and we got very positive responses, although the events coincided
the stock market volatility in Hong Kong," Bodenmuller said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will recover from the financial crisis in Asia faster
than other economies in the region because it has good economic
fundamentals, good financial operation systems, rich foreign
exchange reserves and, above all, a team of financial experts.
</P>
<P>
Bodenmuller said Hong Kong's prospects will be very bright. It can
play a more important role for China because it is a gate for
foreign businessmen to do business with China.
</P>
<P>
"I think Beijing really fulfills its promises to give Hong Kong
a high degree of autonomy," Bodenmuller said.
</P>
<P>
The policy of "one country, two systems" is so far so good.
That is a unique concept, which can also serve as an example for
the other countries and regions to solve the problems left over by
history, he commented.
</P>
<P>
There are around 200 Swiss companies in Hong Kong. The biggest
are the Nestle, a producer of chocolate, cream, food and world
leader for baby milk, and ABB, a combined company between Sweden's
Asean and Switzerland's Brown Boweri, which specializes in power
stations.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland's exports to Hong Kong jumped by 20 percent in the
first 10 months of this year and the imports from Hong Kong
increased by about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bodenmuller, 55, said he loves Hong Kong because this is an
interesting place. His son and daughter have been to Hong Kong
several times and once to Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Hiking is his hobby and he often goes to Lantau Island, Sai
Kung and "every corner of Hong Kong". His another hobby is to
collect pipes. On a table in his office, there are more than 20
pipes from different countries.
</P>
<P>
"One of my regrets is that I have few opportunities to talk to
the ordinary people because I am unable to speak Cantonese. I am
very sorry about this," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
