<HEADLINE> Dhaka Recovers 1.33 Billion Dollar Overdue Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- A total of 59.84 billion taka
(1.33 billion U.S. dollars) of overdue loans were recovered in the
period of January-October this year, the national news agency BSS
reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Bangladeshi Finance Minister Shah AMS
Kibria while addressing a gathering of students and teachers of
the Dhaka University Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the achievement to some stern measures in the
banking sector and the strict supervision of the Bangladesh Bank,
the central bank, by the government.
</P>
<P>
He said that the proportion of overdue loans had come down to
37.87 percent at present from 40.31 percent earlier.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of overdue loans has exceeded 100 billion taka
(2.22 billion dollars), according to local press reports.
</P>
<P>
"The country's overall economic condition is now in a
satisfactory level, and Bangladesh's economy can reach a
respectable position in the world arena through successful
coordination of our natural resources and skilled manpower," the
finance minister said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that credit in the private sector, which was
increasing at a rate of 16.78 percent currently, was "very
satisfactory."
</P>
<P>
Export growth was estimated at 21 percent in the July-September
period this year, he added.
</P>
<P>
The government followed a non-inflation growth strategy, the
minister said, adding "the current rate of inflation is still
below 5 percent."
</P>
<P>
The government has decided to privatize loss-making industries
and national organizations as these industrial units were causing
an annual loss of 25 billion taka (555.6 million dollars), the
finance minister said.
</P>
<P>
But he pointed out that the country's "present foreign exchange
reserves of 1.6 billion dollars were not at a comfortable level."
</P>
</TEXT>
