<HEADLINE> Bosnian Leaders Agree to Common Passport, Citizenship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian leaders attending an
international peace conference here have agreed to introduce a
common passport and citizenship law for their country as a gesture
to implement the Dayton peace accord, diplomatic sources said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which still needs approval of the Bosnian
parliament, had been demanded by German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel and his French counterpart Hubert Vedrine during their
recent trip to Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
However, the Bosnian leaders have not agreed to a common
currency and a common car license plate which had also been sought
by the two foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
The two-day international conference on the implementation of
the Dayton peace accord for Bosnia will be concluded later
Wednesday with the adoption of a final declaration which is
expected to put additional pressure on the Bosnian parties to
comply with the peace agreements in exchange for further Western
help.
</P>
<P>
The conference is also seeking to strengthen the role of
Western mediator Carlos Westendorp to push forward the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting are delegates from 51 countries and 21
international organizations, including Bosnian presidency members,
Alija Izetbegovic, Kresimir Zubak and Momcilo Krajisnik.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel and Westendorp are due to give a joint press conference
after the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
