<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Tackle "Millennium Bug" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 10 (Xinhua) -- South African
Telecommunications Minister Jay Naidoo Tuesday announced a plan
to counter the year of 2000 computer problem, which experts
warned was too late.
</P>
<P>
The potentially disastrous problem, dubbed the "millennium
bug", involves the inability of many computer programs to
recognize the turn of the millennium because years are identified
by only their last two digits.
</P>
<P>
Computers' internal dates will revert to 1900 instead of
moving on to 2000 when the date changes over on December 31,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The worldwide cost on a solution had been estimated at 600
billion U.S. dollars, while the cost to South Africa was
estimated at 25 billion Rand (5.2 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Naidoo told a news conference that a national coordinating
committee would be formed by the end of January next year, using
skills of representatives from both the private and public
sectors.
</P>
<P>
It would oversee six sub-committees focusing on different
sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The national committee would report monthly to a cabinet
ministers' committee, chaired by Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and
convened by Naidoo.
</P>
<P>
An interim committee had drawn up the proposals presented
Tuesday, and would be replaced by a full-time secretariat early
next year, Naidoo said.
</P>
<P>
A complete assessment of computer programs that would be
affected by the millennium bug must completed before April, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Industry has welcomed the initiative, but there is a feeling
that government is doing too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
Year 2000 experts warned that, by now, organizations should be
busy with code conversions, or even beginning to test corrected
codes. Yet the committee is due to complete its assessment of the
size of the problem only by April 1998.
</P>
<P>
It was also doubted that such a massive amount of work could
be done with South Africa's limited resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
