<HEADLINE> Former Thai Central Bank Governor's Bonuses Questioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Thai Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda has been asked to explain why the former governor
of the Central Bank blamed for ruining the country's financial
system was given a huge 'golden handshake.'
</P>
<P>
Former governor of the bank of Thailand Rerngchai Marakanond
was reported to be among a few former top executives of the
Central Bank who are being given huge benefits and annual bonuses,
even though they are allegedly held responsible for the financial
debacle.
</P>
<P>
Chart Pattana Party Spokesman Sunai Julpongsatorn, who lodged a
so-called 'fresh interpellation' on Tuesday, said Tarrin will have
to come up with sound reasons for letting those top executives,
former and present, go unpunished after their 'erratic and
devastating' decisions eventually forced the termination of 56
financial firms on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rerngchai and a few other top executives of the Central Bank
have been accused of causing losses estimated at 430 billion baht
(10.24 billion U.S. dollars) in a vain bid to bail out the
liquidity-strained finance firms.
</P>
<P>
A source said the ex-governor was allowed to pocket 20 million
baht (476,000 dollars) plus a fat bonus despite causing so much
ruin to the financial system of the country. 
</P>
