<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Adobe Kang In Rural Beijing Fast Becoming A Thing Of The Past </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The adobe kangs, that
venerable raised adobe sleeping area in Chinese houses, has
disappeared from 720,000 households in rural parts of Beijing,
where they are replaced by wooden or metal beds.
</P>
<P>
According to Beijing Daily, more prosperous families in the
city's outskirts say that kangs are difficult to find nowadays,
and 90 percent of the peasants there no longer sleep on them.
</P>
<P>
The kang was common in all rural parts of northern
China. Peasants would build a raised area out of sun-dried mud
bricks in part of the southern side of the house. In winter, they
could build a fire under it and use it as a warm bed. And, along
with a wife and children, it came to be considered a basic
condition of a happy life.
</P>
<P>
When visitors came to call, they were invited to sit on the
kang, on which a little wooden table could be set, to serve from.
</P>
<P>
However, the kang is immobile and gets dirty and dusty
easily. So, in the modern age, as peasants got richer, they
changed their kangs into beds.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zhanao, a peasant in the southern suburb of Beijing, said
that after his kang was replaced by a bed, he found that his house
was wider and cleaner. Zhang uses a stove for warmth now, and some
of his neighbors even heat their houses in the same manner as in
urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that more than 200 households in his village have
gotten rid of their kangs, but some old men still refuse to
abandon their warm kangs.
</P>
<P>
According to a Beijing resource conservation office, most
peasants in mountainous areas outside the city still use kangs,
because coal is not available, but they have found ways to improve
the kang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Media Urged To Join AIDS Prevention Crusade in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The mass media can make a
greater contribution to China's AIDS prevention drive by providing
HIV/AIDS information to the public, according to Liu Kangmai, an
expert with the Chinese Academy of Preventative Medicine.
</P>
<P>
Liu told a symposium on HIV/AIDS in China that the media reach
a large audience and have made a contribution to preventing the
spread of HIV (human immunodeficiency virus) infections in China
since the first case was reported in 1985.
</P>
<P>
In a survey in Qingdao City in east China's Shandong Province,
the percentage of people who could correctly answer questions
about HIV/AIDS was 74 percent after newspapers, radio, and
television increased coverage of the disease by 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sales of condoms and books about HIV/AIDS and sexually
transmitted diseases also increased by 55 percent and 49 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Radio and television reach about 85 percent of the Chinese
people. In the 15 provinces and municipalities where the most
serious epidemic of HIV/AIDS in China is reported, the coverage
rate has reached more than 80 percent or almost 100 percent, Liu
said.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health will join some departments next year to
ask national and local media to carry or broadcast programs on the
problem regularly, for free, said Shen Jie, a ministry official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
