<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets With Fijian Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Minister of Foreign Affairs Qian Qichen, in a meeting today with
Berenado Wunibobo, foreign affairs and foreign trade minister of
Fiji, said that Fiji has become one of China's major trade
partners in the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Qian added that the two countries have had good co-operation in
international and regional affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the two countries established diplomatic
relations 22 years ago, bilateral relations have developed
smoothly, and that the two countries have maintained exchanges of
high-ranking officials and have had trade, economic,
technological, cultural, military, and education co-operation.
</P>
<P>
He said that, although great changes have taken place in the
international situation, the two countries have the same task of
developing their economies and improving the standard of living,
and China will enjoy rapid and healthy economic growth for the
next two decades.
</P>
<P>
This is favorable to further developing friendly bilateral
co-operative relations, he said, and maintaining a stable and
healthy relationship is in the interest of the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese Government appreciates the Fijian
government's "one China" stance and that the Chinese side is ready
to join the Fijian government in seizing the current favorable
opportunity to raise bilateral relations to a new level at the
turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Wunibobo said that the two countries have enjoyed good
relations and exchanges in all fields since they established
diplomatic relations and that the Fijian government attaches great
importance to its relations with China, and thanked the Chinese
government and people for their assistance in the past.
</P>
<P>
He said he also appreciates the Chinese government's upholding
of justice and adheres to the principle that all countries, big or
small, are equal in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the Fijian government will adhere to the "one
China" policy.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also discussed expanding bilateral
economic and trade co-operation and increasing exchanges and
co-operation in agriculture, fisheries, education and tourism.
</P>
<P>
They also signed the Agreement Between the Government of the
People's Republic of China and the Government of the Sovereign
Democratic Republic of Fiji Relating to Civil Air Transport.
</P>
