<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Limits Prawning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The government has ordered to
limit prawning along the central Mozambique's Sofala bank to
protect the prawn resources in the region, a senior official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Agostinho do Rosario, Agriculture and Fishing Minister
said here Tuesday that the government has decided to reduce the
annual prawning time to 180,000 hours from 270,000 hours, and put
the maximum prawning capacity at 80 million tons a year.
</P>
<P>
The government has also decided to stop issuing prawning
license and encourage prawn cultivation.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made in line with the demand of the
Mozambican Fishing Institute and the Mozambique Fishermen's
Association.
</P>
<P>
There are 64 registered prawning boats along the Sofala bank,
which produces 90 percent of the country's prawn export.
</P>
<P>
Prawn is mozambique's no. one export commodity. The country
exported 54 million tons of prawns in the first half of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
