<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholars Expecting Return of Lost Dunhuang Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- With the upcoming 100th
anniversary of the discovery of the Dunhuang scriptures cave, some
Chinese scholars are expecting the return of lost relics to the
motherland, the "People's Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Dunhuang cave was found in Gansu Province in the year
1900. In the early years of the discovery foreigners flocked there
to obtain a multitude of ancient books and other relics at
exceptionally low prices.
</P>
<P>
The cave contained 40,000 to 50,000 volumes of writings,
including approximately 30,000 volumes in Chinese and more than
10,000 volumes in Tibetan, the newspaper said, plus about 1,000
paintings.
</P>
<P>
To date, there are 300 volumes at the Dunhuang Research
Institute, with others scattered in a number of Chinese cities.
More than three-fourths of the lost relics are believed to be in
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
For the past century, scholars around the world have devoted
their lives to Dunhuang studies. However, some Chinese researchers
and specialists have lamented over microfilms from foreign museums.
</P>
<P>
The cave is viewed not only as a site to exhibit the glamor of
China's splendid academic history, but also a place of humiliation
in its early years.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scholars, who are engaged in Dunhuang and relevant
studies, met at Beijing University recently to appeal for the
return of Dunhuang relics.
</P>
<P>
At the weekend forum, scholars said that the return of lost
relics are more significant to protecting the integration of human
civilization than legal issues of ownership.
</P>
<P>
Dunhuang studies have become popular around the world, but the
relics' brilliance belongs to the motherland, scholars said.
</P>
<P>
Ji Xianlin, a well-known scholar with Beijing University, noted
that there are four leading culture systems around the
world: Chinese, Indian, Muslim and Europeans. The paintings and
books at Dunhuang resulted in the melting of cultures.
</P>
<P>
"How to make them display a bigger role, and how to better
study and protect them should be the common cause of the entire
world," the newspaper quoted Ji as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to Fan Jinshi, deputy director of the Dunhuang Relics
Research Institute, the return of lost relics could be difficult
for foreigners long have held that the relics had been rightfully
purchased.
</P>
<P>
"But people with the least common sense can see that the meager
money was not enough to afford even one item," Fan said, adding
that the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) imperial government at that
time, though weak and corrupt, had issued orders to seal the
relics.
</P>
<P>
Celebrations will be held in the year 2000 to mark the 100th
anniversary of the discovery of the scriptures cave, and some of
the lost Dunhuang relics could be shown in the motherland even if
they are not returned by that time, Fan said. 
</P>
