<HEADLINE> Chinese Courts Amend Misjudgements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- China is taking steps to
rectify errors in the judicial system throughout the country,
according to a story in today's "Legal Daily."
</P>
<P>
Between January and October, the courts of central Henan
Province affirmed misjudgements in 94 cases concerning 146 court
officials who made mistakes, the Beijing-based newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The province's Higher People's Court corrected five misjudged
cases by punishing a vice-president, an assistant judge and other
three officials in a local court who accepted bribes.
</P>
<P>
The Intermediate People's Court in Zhuhai City, southern
Guangdong Province, is seeking a better mechanism for effectively
checking trial errors. The city's special court, established six
years ago, has reviewed more than 380 cases on appeal. Of those,
71 were re-tried and 45 judgements were amended, the story said.
</P>
