<HEADLINE> Gold Price Slipped to 18-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- As the price of gold bullion
slipped to an 18-year low overnight, local gold producers cut
short the life of its mines.
</P>
<P>
Overnight in New York, the gold price reached an 18-year low,
hitting 281.35 U.S. dollars an ounce, overall the gold index
closed down 26.7 points, or 3.04 percent at 851.1.
</P>
<P>
In Sydney, the spot price of gold bullion dropped 4.85 U.S.
dollars closed today at 284.00 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gold casualties include Aurora Gold, which shed 10 cents, or
7.69 percent, and Central Norseman, which lost seven cents, or
15.91 percent.
</P>
<P>
As the stock market weakened, the head of Normandy Mining Ltd,
Australia's largest gold producer, predicted "very tough times
ahead" for the local gold industry.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously that can't go on for very long and you'll see a lot
of mines close down," Normandy's chairman Robert Champion de
Crespigny said over ABC radio.
</P>
<P>
His prediction was given credibility by Goldfields Kalgoorlie
Ltd, which announced it had cut short the life of its Paddington
mine in Western Australia by 18 months.
</P>
<P>
However, the stockbrokers and analysts saw there was a brighter
side to the story, "It suggests that companies are starting to
believe that the gold price is close to some sort of turning
point," they said.
</P>
<P>
They argued that the laws of supply and demand are such that
reduced production would start to push the price up at some point.
</P>
<P>
But sentiment could push the price down further temporarily,
they admitted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
