<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Better Social Insurance System Needed for Laid-off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is
trying to reassure laid-off workers by establishing a public
welfare system, a "People's Daily" story said today.
</P>
<P>
Most laid-off workers favor re-employment with state-run
businesses, but dislike working in any non-public enterprises,
some of which provide good benefits, the story said.
</P>
<P>
A bankrupt distillery refused a proposed merger with a township
business, which did not offer a pension insurance system.
Laid-off distillery workers feared that they would not receive
housing, medical benefits and pension insurance, the story said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese enterprises long have pursued the policy of "lifelong
jobs, high perks but low wages," and government-controlled
production, profit allocation and employees' wages in the planned
economy. Thus, the state-owned enterprises, actually representing
the government were held responsible for compensating the laid-off
workers.
</P>
<P>
However, most businesses on the edge of bankruptcy, cannot
afford to continue traditional welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
The deepening reform should be closely linked with all the
supportive reforms. A sound social welfare system will safeguard
any further reform in the market economy, the story said.
</P>
<P>
Some of the younger laid-off workers in the Jixi Mineral
Resources Bureau, in northeastern Heilongjiang Province, however,
voluntarily chose farming instead of jobs in another factory.
</P>
<P>
The bureau promised to maintain their medical and housing
benefits, and provide them with low-interest loans and 60 percent
of wages for the first six months after being laid off.
</P>
<P>
The country has extensively boosted unemployment insurance and
pensions in state-run enterprises, the story added. But, except
for the two items mentioned above, China has yet to establish
social pools for other insurance.
</P>
<P>
Some local governments have adopted a different financial
pooling proportion between businesses' accounts and personal
accounts in various industries.
</P>
<P>
Experts suggested that the country should set up a uniform
social insurance system covering the state-funded, collective,
foreign-funded, township and non-public enterprises, the story
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
