<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lead Poisoning: A Threat To Beijing Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- A recent study found that
nearly 70 percent of the children in Beijing suffer from some form
of lead poisoning because of polluted air and other causes.
</P>
<P>
Lead in chidren's bodies can affect their nervous, circulatory,
and digestive systems, according to Prof. Ding Zongyi, head of the
survey group.
</P>
<P>
The study also showed that even small amounts of lead in the
blood can stunt a child's intelligence, according to today's
Beijing Youth Daily. Things like height, weight, and chest
measurement decrease as the amount of lead in the blood goes up,
says Prof. Ding.
</P>
<P>
Children who suffer from lead poisoning are also more prone to
ill-tempered and aggressive behavior and are more likely to suffer
from respiratory diseases, anemia, urinary infections, and even
renal failure, he said.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that automobile exhaust, preserved eggs, and fruit
peel can all be sources of lead pollution, and that the lead
contained in pencils, paint, and the colored covers of textbooks
is not up to safety standards. Even the lead in some brands of
crayons is enough to cause poisoning.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Children's Hospital has already started lead
poisoning tests for children in nearby areas and will soon set up
a special center for treating lead poisoning in its new emergency
treatment center, the paper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Increasing Per Capita Floor Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Per capita housing space in
Beijing has increased from 1992's 11.3 sq.m. to 13.8 sq.m.,
according to a recent study.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, Beijing has built more than 38 million
sq.m. of new housing, improving the living conditions of 700,000
families, much of that on the outskirts of the city.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has decided to build ten more housing
sites in suburban areas, with six to be completed by the end of
this year, according to the Municipal Urban and Rural Construction
Committee.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city has pulled down 2.89 million sq.m. of
shabby housing in the past five years and moved at least 8,500
families from these aging houses.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the city has given priority to improving the living
conditions of people with special difficulties and has built 1.88
million sq.m. of housing for them, and has seen to it that any
whose per capita living space is less than 4 sq.m. can move into
new housing by the end of the century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
