<HEADLINE> French Gaullist RPR Chief Sharpens Attack on Jospin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 10 (Xinhua) -- President of the Gaullist Rally
for the Republic (RPR) Philippe Seguin Wednesday accused the
Socialist Party of sharing "exactly the same objective" with the
far-right National Front (FN), which is to eliminate the
mainstream right-wing parties from the political life of France.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Europe-1 TV station, Seguin said that
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin is copying late President Francois
Mitterrand's old strategy of "making rise the FN to weaken the
(rightwing) opposition."
</P>
<P>
He said that the "visible wish of the prime minister would be
to weaken the function of the president."
</P>
<P>
Seguin, who described the system of cohabitation between the
president and the prime minister as "not a good regime," accused
Jospin of "trying to develop a theory of two heads of executive,
of a bicephalous system, of two consuls put on an equal stand in
the style of the ancient Rome."
</P>
<P>
But he also expressed reserve over the suggestion on re-writing
the French Constitution to make the presidential and legislative
elections take place at the same time.
</P>
<P>
"If you want to organize the simultaneity of the presidential
and legislative elections, you enter a regime of American style.
Are we ready, I don't think so," he said.
</P>
<P>
On whether the RPR will rally with the FN in the regional and
cantonal elections to be held in March 1998, Seguin said the
Gaullist party would not ally with "the men whose vowed objective
is to eliminate us from the political life." 
</P>
</TEXT>
