<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Leader, President Meet Saudi Crown Prince </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran's supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei and President Mohammad Khatami have met
Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz, with both sides
pledging to further bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The meetings were held Tuesday night at the sidelines of the
ongoing Islamic summit, which brought together leaders and
ranking officials of the 55-member Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC), according to the official news agency IRNA
today.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah's visit to Tehran is the first such visit by a Saudi
leader in about two decades. Post-Islamic revolution Iran had
called on Saudi Muslims to rise and topple the monarch and later
Riyadh sided with Baghdad in its eight-year war with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic relations between the two countries had been
severed off after hundreds of protesting Iranian pilgrims were
killed in the holy city of Mecca in 1987 during a clash with the
Saudi police.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei told the Saudi crown prince that Iran has no real
problem with any of the Islamic countries, and there is a vast
potential for cooperation, the materialization of which depends
on the two countries' resolve.
</P>
<P>
Iranian-Saudi cooperation is instrumental in promoting OIC
goals of unity and solidarity, he added.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei admitted that there are numerous problems facing the
Muslim world, but accused "enemies of Islam" of sowing discord
and fabricating most of the problems. Through unity and
unbending resolve of the Muslim states, he said, many of those
problems can be settled.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah expressed hope that through bilateral efforts, the
problems between the two countries would be resolved.
</P>
<P>
Khatami told Abdullah that appropriate time has come for the
two big Muslim countries to start a new round of relations,
citing unity and coordination as a need.
</P>
<P>
He deemed Abdullah's visit as a "harbinger of good omen" for
the two countries' future relationship and the region in the
years to come.
</P>
<P>
The holding of the Islamic summit in Tehran offered Iran an
unparalleled opportunity to carry out diplomatic efforts to woo
regional countries and reach out for the Arab and Islamic world
as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
