<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Opens up New Dimensions to Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Africa, a continent which is
often seen as the last frontier for information technology, where
radios are still the main source of communication with the
outside world in most of its rural areas, is now forging ahead by
getting itself wired up on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
For Africa, a continent with the least developed
infrastructure, namely only two percent of the world's
telephones, Internet service has undoutbly offered a "jump-start"
opportunity to narrow its gap with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Currently 47 of the 54 countries in Africa have developed some
form of Internet access - either a local dial-up store and
forward E-mail service with a gateway to the Internet, or a full
leased line service, said Michael Jensen, who is considered as
the "father of Internet in Africa" through his Internet-related
work in 29 African countries over the last 11 years.
</P>
<P>
Of these, he added, 42 countries and territories have achieved
live Internet public access service in their capital cities.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it is not surprising to see name cards or
advertisements carried in newspapers now with E-mail addressed to
the time-honored postal and physical addresses.
</P>
<P>
This telecommunications marvel has just started to infiltrate
into various sectors of the economy. Tanzania has placed its
tourism atttractions on the Internet, the Sukuma Museum in the
country recently became the first museum in east Africa, and
probably in the entire sub- Saharan region to offer visitors
virtual tours via the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, manufacturers seeking to export to the Common Market
for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) member countries may
soon benifit from a new computer service by making use of an
E-mail system that functions via the local area network.
</P>
<P>
In Namibia, the Ministry of Environment and Tourism has
invested in an on-line booking system, which will enable customer
queries and reservations to be processed in minutes.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, the "technology-hungry country" which has the
most advanced telecommunications network on the continent, is
even providing services like Internet banking in the country,
which is well ahead of the information-rich the United States,
according to Amolo Ng'weno, an executive from Africaonline, a
multi-national Internet provider headquartered in S. Africa.
</P>
<P>
Ng'weno, who is based in Nairobi, Kenya, said there are 150 to
200 Internet service providers in Africa, in which 70 are
stationed in S.Africa.
</P>
<P>
Africaonline, the premier Internet company in Kenya which was
founded in 1994, now has approximately 6,000 subscribers in the
country, 95 percent of which are small and medium-sized
businesses. In Ghana, Cote d'Ivoire, Tanzania and Zimbabwe, the
company has another 6,000 users to its services. and the number
is still increasing by 10 percent a month.
</P>
<P>
"The nice things about the service," said Ng'weno, "are that
businesses see an immediate return both in reduced communication
cost and in finding things they need. It's very exciting to see
people interacting internationally and easily."
</P>
<P>
The picture in South Africa is much brighter than in the rest
of the continent. It is estimated that the number of South
Africans on line was about 500,000 in September, and could reach
one million by the end of this year. The country now ranks 14th
in the world concerning domain names, leaving behind some first
world countries such as New Zealand, Denmark and Austria.
</P>
<P>
A recent study by International Data Corporation shows that 71
percent of South Africa's top 200 organizations have set up a web
server or are planning to do so.
</P>
<P>
What is more, on-line advertising is the largest component of
Internet electronic commerce. By the end of the century, the
South African internet site development and advertisingmarket
could be worth one billion Rand (222 million U.S. dollars) with
more than two million Rand (about 44,4000 US dollars) of on-line
transactions a year, noted Robin Parker, a Web publisher.
</P>
<P>
No wonder studies by the Geneva-based International
Telecommunications Union (ITU) and the World Bank indicate a
direct link between effecient telecommunications and economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
However, on-line advertising is still making a minimal impact
in Africa, with a possible total of no more than around US$20,000
a month on popular websites, said Arthur Goldstuck, an expert
on Internet business, adding 90 percent of this spending is
probably taking place in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Commercial transactions which currently involves mainly
travel, books magazines, records &AMP; Cds, cars and property &AMP; real
estate, are believed to be taking a long time to take off.
</P>
<P>
Internet, which takes a phone line and a computer unit for a
user to cruise down the world informations superhighway, has
confronted some major obstacles in Africa, namely the "existing
telephone infrastructure and regulations in the telephone
industry", noted Ng'weno.
</P>
<P>
Africa still has the slowest growth in the number of telephone
lines per 100 people of anywhere in the world. Sub-Sahara Africa
has an average of just 0.48 telephone lines per 100 people. Yet
the number of people waiting for a phone line is reported to be
growing at 7 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
With 12 percent of the world's population, Africa has only two
percent of the world's telephones, compared with other regions of
the world -- Latin America has six percent of the lines and eight
percent of the population and Asia, 13 percent of the lines with
57 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
The ITU estimates it will cost in excess of US$28 billion to
increase sub-Saharan teledensity levels to one line per 100
people by the year 2000. With individual nations unable to meet
the cost, it is suggested that the example of Ivory Coast and
Ghana be followed, which is to inject private capital combined
with a relaxation of regulatory environments.
</P>
<P>
It is encouraging to note that some African countries have
made telecommunications a priority and are installing digital
switches with fibre optic inter-city backbones and newest
cellular and mobile technology.
</P>
<P>
These would consequently give a great push-up for net service
on the continent.
</P>
<P>
"Internet business is nothing now, but it's growing quickly.
And its' a business that can only grow," said Ng'weno, who
believed the prospects for Internet are enormous.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
