<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Visa to Launch Asia's First Electronic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's
Telecommunications Corporation and Visa, an international card
payment company, today signed here an agreement to jointly launch
Asia-Pacific's first pilot program to carry out business and
retail transactions over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The program, named Borderless Marketing-Electronic Commerce
(BMEC), the first in Asia Pacific, will be completed in nine
months under the auspices of Malaysia's Multimedia Development
Corporation (MDC), according to officials here.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's Ministry of Energy, Telecommunications and Posts has
been charged with the responsibility to appoint a controller and
to set up a certificate authority for electronic commerce, MDC's
chief operating officer Mohamed Arif Nun said.
</P>
<P>
Eight banks are now undergoing some formality procedure to team
up with the BMEC program.
</P>
<P>
The BMEC program will provide the project framework and
infrastructure for the subsequent roll-out of the electronic
commerce in Malaysia which is the first country in Asia-Pacific to
perform a business-to-business Visa electronic commerce, said
David Lee, chief administration officer for Asia Pacific
representing Visa International at the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Lee said the program would also allow service and technology
providers in Malaysia's Multimedia Super Corridor to develop new
business models and experiment various electronic
commerce-enabling tools and applications that bring customers and
sellers together.  
</P>
</TEXT>
