<HEADLINE> Kenya to Be Tough over Dumping: VP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Vice-President George
Saitoti has said that his government would take necessary
measures including enacting anti-dumping legislation to protect
local industries.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation today quoted the vice-president as saying
Tuesday that Kenya would not allow the dumping of
highly-subsidized imports into the country.
</P>
<P>
He noted that some countries were employing "predatory
tactics" in penetrating into the Kenyan market by subsidizing
their export products.
</P>
<P>
Saitoti reaffirmed that the government was committed to
fair-play and is, therefore, using non-tariff barriers to create
a level playing field for all industrialists in the East African
country.
</P>
<P>
Measures to be taken are aimed at providing suitable
environment for the private sector to take the lead in economic
development in the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion to mark the 75th anniversary of Kenya
Breweries Ltd. (KBL), Jeremiah Kiereini, KBL Chairman, said that
Kenyan beer produced by his company had not been able to
penetrate into the South African market due to the high taxes
demanded by the local authorities.
</P>
<P>
He complained that while Kenya opens its doors to foreign
products, South Africa does not reciprocate. 
