<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Market Offers Employment for Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 10 (Xinhua) -- More and more people in China
now turn to the labor market for employment instead of government
appointment, as the country's economic restructuring has made it
possible for the market to play a dominant role in this aspect.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang Province in east China is a good example. By now it
has established more than 1,000 labor service intermediary
agencies, which provided employment services for over three
million urban and rural laborers in the past five years. And 2.6
million of them have found jobs as a result.
</P>
<P>
The province has taken steps to reform its government-dominated
employment and personnel systems, and given employers and
employees two-way choices.
</P>
<P>
Labor markets also play a role in helping laid-off workers find
new jobs. Some 80 percent of the more than 100,000 laid-offs in
the province, who have been reemployed over the past few years,
benefited from market services.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang has also opened 90 markets for professionals,
including a provincial-level personnel market and a state-level
market for rural enterprise professionals. The markets have helped
120,000 technicians and managers sign contracts with employers.
</P>
<P>
Some labor service agencies and personnel markets also offer
necessary training for workers.
</P>
<P>
The province is working to set up a labor information network
and to link it up with the national network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
