<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Loans For Environmental Protection In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- A World Bank-funded sewage
treatment project began yesterday on the Chaoyangxi River in
Nanning, capital of southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
The project is part of a comprehensive water treatment program
costing 200 million U.S. dollars, with half of it from World Bank
loans.
</P>
<P>
The 14-km river, which has 280,000 people living along its
banks, has been referred to as "Black River" because of the
serious industrial pollution and residential waste in it. The
waste treatment project will use 48 million U.S. dollars of WB
loans and 400 million yuan (48 million U.S. dollars) of city
government funds, which will also be used for a waste treatment
facility with a 240,000 to 480,000 ton daily capacity.
</P>
<P>
Other projects will include Lijiang River in Guilin, a famous
scenic spot, and some other rivers severely polluted by sugar
mills. Guangxi is China's largest sugar producer.
</P>
<P>
The work is scheduled to be completed by the year 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
