<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer-Managed Residential Quarter in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Qian Ming, a Shanghai
resident, has never brought the keys to his apartment with himself
since he moved into his new house, for whenever he comes back
home, a light press on the door lock is enough for him to enter
his cozy apartment.
</P>
<P>
As a resident of the second Youdian village in Hongkou
district, the first computer-managed residential quarter in
Shanghai, Qian has been enjoying a lot of convenience brought
about by the computer management.
</P>
<P>
With a total investment of 20 million yuan (about 2.4 million
US dollars), the Municipal Post and Telecommunication
Administration built the quarter into computer-managed one in
November, and 300 of the quarter's total 1,200 households have
taken the lead in hooking up to the quarter's computer network
center.
</P>
<P>
At the entrance of the residential quarter, the traffic flow is
managed by a computer, and a large screen was erected broadcasting
weather information and news. All major roads within the quarter
are equipped with monitors to ensure security.
</P>
<P>
The computer center of the network is the nucleus of the whole
system, taking charge of the system's maintenance, design, and
monitoring.
</P>
<P>
Through the network, residents can pay bills for gas, water,
and electricities; be alarmed at gas leaking, enjoy music, and
receive medical treatment. Small amount of fees are needed for the
service.
</P>
<P>
The second-phase computer management project has also been
launched for the quarter, and is expected to be completed by the
second half of next year. When it is completed, people can hook up
to the Internet, and enjoy video-on-demand service at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
