<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Weakens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar is
plummeting with a distinct lack of buying interest driving the
currency to new depths.
</P>
<P>
Today, the Australian dollar closed at 66.75, after dropping to
a new four year low of 66.48 earlier in the session. It was at
66.90 US cents late yesterday.
</P>
<P>
ANZ head of foreign exchange sales John Reedyk said the local
unit was last at these levels in December 1993. The previous low
was 64.10 US cents in September 1993.
</P>
<P>
"Exporters are taking a back seat and seeing what happens -
they are generally the buyers in the Aussie market, so they are
notable by their absence," Reedyk said.
</P>
<P>
The price of gold reached an 18-year low overnight in New York,
hitting 281.35 US dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
Adding to the pressure on the local currency today, the South
Korean won fell to a record low against the US dollar after the
South Korean government suspended operations of another five
merchant banks.
</P>
<P>
Against the yen this evening, the Australian dollar finished at
86.69 from 87.24 yesterday. It was also at 1.1958 marks, from
1.1979.  
</P>
</TEXT>
