<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Down On Wall Street Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
finished the day on a low note, buffeted by a fall on Wall Street
and a further plunge in the price of gold.
</P>
<P>
Brisbane-based Nevitts broker Ivan Mitchell said the softer
market was due to a combination of factors including a weakening
of resource stocks, a poor finish for the Dow and drops in Tokyo
and Hong Kong markets.
</P>
<P>
The plummet of the gold price to an 18-year low overnight added
to the negativity, a Sydney-based broker said.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries closed down 28.1 points at 2554.7 after
spiraling down 25.3 points just after the open.
</P>
<P>
Overnight the Dow Jones Industrial Average closed down 61.18
points at 8,049.66.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index finished the day down 35.9 points at
4374.2 while the all resources dropped 23.1 points at 1104.1.
</P>
<P>
Spot gold bullion was trading at 283.70 US dollars, down 2.20.
</P>
<P>
Among the leading resource stocks, diversified giant BHP was
down 37 cents while Rio Tinto lost 19.3.
</P>
<P>
In the industrial stocks, Rupert Murdoch's News Corp was down
one while its preferred shares were 12 cents lower.
</P>
<P>
The banking index dropped 52.9 points to 5351.9, with National
Australia Bank leading the charge by losing 26.5 cents, ANZ shed
10 cents, Commonwealth Bank was down eight and Westpac fell nine
cents.
</P>
<P>
The insurance index remained in positive territory, defying the
general negative trend and closing at 6328.3.
</P>
<P>
QBE closed up 12 cents and National Mutual Holdings edged up
four to end the day's trade.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 322.97 million by volume, valued at
833.40 million Australian dollars (550 Million US dollars), with
falls outnumbering rises 649 to 381.  
</P>
</TEXT>
