<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Moves to Stop PNA Census in Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli government is
hoping to pass special legislation today to prevent the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) from conducting its census
in eastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The PNA census is scheduled to begin today throughout the
territories under PNA control.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli ministerial committee had approved amending a law on
activities in eastern Jerusalem Tuesday night to give Public
Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani the legal authority to prevent
the census in Jerusalem, Israel's only English newspaper The
Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The amendment is to be put to a cabinet vote by phone, and
then brought before the Knesset (parliament) for approval today.
</P>
<P>
Ophir Pines, who co-chairs the Jerusalem caucus in the
Knesset, has written to Faisal Husseini, PNA Minister for
Jerusalem Affairs, to ask him to refrain from carrying out the
census in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Pines said the census is an unwarranted provocation, and it
would be better to discuss Jerusalem's status in the talks on
the permanent arrangements, rather than try to create facts on
the ground regarding sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Tuesday instructed
Kahalani to prevent the PNA from carrying out the census in
eastern Jerusalem. He said that a Palestinian census in the city
violated the peace accords that give the Palestinians limited
autonomy in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
"It is unacceptable to us that in the sovereign state of
Israel, a foreign body is trying to undermine our sovereignty,"
Netanyahu said. "This is a gross violation of an agreement, and
I have asked Minister Kahalani to thwart the attempts by the
Palestinians" to carry out the census in Jerusalem, he added.
</P>
<P>
But PNA Higher Education Minister Hanan Ashrawi said that "the
question of Jerusalem now is not one that needs
interpretation: it is not under Israeli sovereignty; it is
legally a part of Palestinian territories, and therefore the
census should cover Jerusalem and will cover Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
Some 4,500 field workers today will begin collecting the
500,000 copies of the 78-question census which were mailed last
month, according to Hassan Abu Libdeh, director of the
Palestinian Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
"This is a big day," Libdeh said. "I am giving the
Palestinian people a very clear message: if we are to use our
resources in a better way, to go into the 21st century in better
shape, we have to use our resources, more wisely, and we must
take part in the census."
</P>
<P>
Libdeh did not confirm whether the census would also take
place in eastern Jerusalem, saying only that the PNA has the
right to do so.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, throughout the West Bank and Gaza, a census
campaign was kicked off with marches to raise public awareness.
</P>
<P>
In the West Bank city of Hebron, some 1,000 census takers,
boy scouts, and the mayor walked through the streets carrying
banners declaring, "the census is the way to build our state."
</P>
<P>
Volunteers distributed posters, bumper stickers and baseball
caps with slogans such as "Another step toward the building of
independent Palestine" and "Contribute to the success of the '97
census." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Enter Aged Society in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- China will enter an aged
society in the year 2000, an expert says.
</P>
<P>
Tian Xueyuan, director of the Population Institute of the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, told Xinhua here today that
people aged at and over 65 will account for seven percent of the
total Chinese population at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
That means China will be defined as a society of senior
citizens according to a UN criterion, the scholar notes.
</P>
<P>
In 1982 Chinese people aged over 65 accounted for 4.9 percent
of the total population, and the rate reached 6.8 percent in
1996. About one-third of Chinese provinces and municipalities,
including Beijing, Shanghai and Sichuan, have entered the aged
society, according to Tian.
</P>
<P>
He attributes the situation to China's birth control policy
which leads to the drop of the birth rate, making young people
accounting for a smaller proportion in the population.
</P>
<P>
Tian notes that the change will cause great impacts on China in
many aspects, including welfare, family structure, traditional
morality and employment.
</P>
<P>
He suggests that the government adopt measures to deal with the
situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
