<HEADLINE> Price Cuts Allow More Chinese to Buy Automobiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Price reductions on
Chinese-made mini-cars and mini-vans with 1.0-liter engines are
making autos more affordable for Chinese families.
</P>
<P>
Alto cars made in Chongqing have been reduced by nearly 10,000
yuan, while Tianjin-made Xiali cars are 3,000-to-5,000 yuan
cheaper.
</P>
<P>
Yunque cars made in Guizhou Province are the first Chinese-made
autos to be priced below 50,000 yuan, what analysts call the
"purchasing point of family cars."
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that of the 70,000 minis sold in Beijing this
year, 90 percent were purchased by individuals.
</P>
<P>
Tian Weisheng, vice president of Tianjin Auto Industry Sales
Co., Ltd., said people had long been talking about "cars entering
Chinese families," but a remarkable rise of auto sales will be
unlikely if the gap between actual purchasing power and price is
not narrowed.
</P>
<P>
To address the problem, some automakers are tapping market
potential by initiating loan policies.
</P>
<P>
In a program between Chongqing Alto and a Beijing sales
partner, 200 Alto cars were sold in just five days as buyers only
had to pay a down payment of 18,000 yuan with the remainder due in
18 months.
</P>
<P>
Other automakers followed suit. In Beijing, an average of a
dozen Xiali cars are sold every day, and no loan agreements have
been broken.
</P>
<P>
Mini-cars are expected to improve sales next year. Purchases by
individuals are estimated at 50 percent of total sales.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
