<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Govt Withdraws Income Tax Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe government
Tuesday formerly withdrew the proposal to impose the levy of five
percent of individual and corporate income tax but refused to
withdraw the other three taxes now already in force.
</P>
<P>
In a ministerial statement in parliament, Finance Minister
Herbert Murerwa said the government had accepted the resolution
of the ruling Zanu (PF) annual conference, the views of the
general public and parliament.
</P>
<P>
"I therefore announce that the proposed five percent war
veterans levy on individual and corporate income tax stands
removed," Murerwa said.
</P>
<P>
The levy together with increases on sales tax on goods, fuel
tax and electricity tax were introduced through the finance No. 2
bill which was brought before parliament last month.
</P>
<P>
The proposals met with stiff opposition from the ruling
party's members of parliament who blocked it from passing, as
well as workers countrywide led by the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade
Unions who Tuesday took to the streets in mass protest.
</P>
<P>
In the mass protest which turned violent, at least 12 vehicles
were destroyed and one police officer injured seriously, and the
entire commercial activity in nearly all of the country's major
cities was forced to stop.  
</P>
</TEXT>
