<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Poverty Alleviation in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Though the Sri Lankan
government has for many years targeted poverty alleviation as one
of its top priorities, much remains to be done in the country's
efforts to phase out the serious social problem.
</P>
<P>
Basically a traditional agriculture country, Sri Lanka has no
solid industrial base to provide enough jobs to its large labor
force. The country of 18.5 million people has an unemployment rate
of 10.5 percent at present.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the country adopted free economic policies and
opened up to the outside in 1978, the gap between the rich and the
poor has been broadened while the national economy got boosted.
</P>
<P>
Realizing the seriousness of the social problem, the Sri Lankan
government carried out the Janasaviya Plan in October 1989 to
alleviate poverty.
</P>
<P>
The plan was part of the economic development strategy of the
government in its bid to create more jobs and increase incomes for
the people.
</P>
<P>
The government offered 2,500 Rupees (42 U.S. dollars) as relief
and employment funds to each of the selected poor families, which,
upon obtaining the funds, were required to get rid of poverty in
two years by way of self-employment.
</P>
<P>
The plan was carried out in five phases from 1989 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the plan brought certain benefits to the
poor under the then government of president Ranasinghe Premadasa.
</P>
<P>
However, the plan lost its momentum after the president was
assassinated in a bomb explosion in Colombo on May 1, 1993.
</P>
<P>
In August, 1995, the present People's Alliance government
assumed office and renamed the Janasaviya Plan as the Samurdhi
Movement.
</P>
<P>
Till the end of 1996, the government had released 34 million
dollars of relief fund and 12 million dollars of employment fund
to 27,000 poor families.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan parliament passed a package of provisions
concerning the Samurdhi Movement last February in an effort to
boost the campaign. The provisions helped the government
strengthen its supervision over poverty alleviation activities.
</P>
<P>
Poverty alleviation organizations were set up at all levels
throughout Sri Lanka and a national poverty eradication committee
was established comprising President Chandrika Kumaratunga, Prime
Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike and several other cabinet
ministers.
</P>
<P>
According to government statistics, poor people still account
for 70 percent of the total population in Sri Lanka. Among them,
more than a quarter, or 325,000 to 390,000 people, are living
below the poverty line -- a fact which can never be neglected.
</P>
<P>
In view of the problem, the government has stepped up
propaganda to help the poor build confidence in shaking off their
own problems.
</P>
<P>
Rural youths are organized to participate in social activities
or development projects while women are encouraged to make
handicraft.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government conducted surveys in rural areas to
collect first-hand information on the current poverty situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. Africa Has Vast Investment Market: Stockbroker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The East African region has
become an emerging market with vast opportunities for investors,
the East African Standard quoted a leading stockbroker as saying.
</P>
<P>
John Munge told the daily newspaper that the region comprising
of Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda had a trade deficit of about two
billion U.S. Dollars a year which means that investor can
comfortably put their money in industries which produce import
substitution goods, the stockbroker added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that investment opportunities in agriculture
and agro-based industries were enormous as agriculture accounts
for 65 percent of the region's export earnings and 70 percent of
the labour force.
</P>
<P>
There is room for investment if only agricultural products are
processed for local consumption, Munge noted.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the region's stock markets can be used as
vehicles to raise funds for long-term investments and the Nairobi
Stock Exchange (NSE) had raised 104 million U.S. Dollars through
divestiture of 207 non-strategic enterprises.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Dar es Salaam Stock Exchange (DSE) and the
Uganda Securities Exchange (USE) would be operational some time
next year.
</P>
<P>
According to Munge, Tanzania has even greater potential as the
listings are expected to include Tanzania Breweries, Tanzania
Cigarette Company, British Petroleum Tanzania, Agip Petroleum and
Tanzania Electric Supply Company.
</P>
<P>
Munge argued that emerging stock markets become unstable when
foreign investment capital is higher than its local component.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the current turmoil in southeast Asian
markets had left the NSE largely untouched because it is mainly
driven by local capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
