<HEADLINE> Collectively Owned Chinese Firm Seeks Listing in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Enwei Group in Chengdu is
seeking to be listed next year on the New York Stock Exchange in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
If approved, this would be the first Chinese collectively-owned
enterprise to be listed abroad.
</P>
<P>
The listing serves two principal aims, said Xue Yongxin,
president of the group: raising funds from expanding international
market and introducing traditional Chinese medicine to other
countries.
</P>
<P>
The listing has been approved by the Sichuan provincial
government and the provincial commission of foreign trade and
economic cooperation. The company is negotiating with
international financial institutions concerning the listing.
</P>
<P>
The Enwei Group plans to explore markets in India, Vietnam,
Indonesia, Germany, South Africa and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The group was jointly founded in 1986 by eight families.
</P>
<P>
Aikangning, developed and produced by the group, is an
inhibitor of many kinds of cancer cells, HIV virustatic and the
hepatitis B virus. Changshoubao, another medicine, is effective on
fatigue syndrome, dizziness, weak eyesight, knee pain and sexual
dysfunction caused by asthenia.
</P>
<P>
The group was granted an ISO-9001 certificate of international
quality. The group employs 20,000 and raised its annual output
vale of 10 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
