<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's current account surplus in October surged 220
percent from a year earlier to 1,081.3 billion yen (about 8.3
billion dollars), the Finance Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Exports increased by 16.9 percent to 4,507.5 billion yen (about
34.8 billion dollars), while imports, in contrast, showed a
marginal growth of 0.7 percent to 3,299.7 billion yen (about 25.5
billion dollars), according to a preliminary report from the
ministry, which attributed the sharp increase to strong exports
aided by the weak yen against the U.S. dollar and weak imports.
(Japan-Current-Account-Surplus)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- A commuter plane crashed in central Canada Tuesday,
killing three people and injuring 14 others, television reports
here said.
</P>
<P>
There were two pilots and 15 passengers on board when the plane
crashed about 100 meters off the end of the runway while trying to
land in "icy, misty" weather. (Canada-Plane-Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- A second round of presidential elections will be
held on December 21, the Serbian Election Committee announced here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the final results released by the committee, none
of the seven candidates won the threshold 50 percent of the votes
in the first round of election held on December 7. Serbian Foreign
Minister Milan Milutinovic, of Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic's ruling Socialist Party, and Vojislav Seseji of the
Radical Party took the lead, pocketing 43.7 percent and 32.19
percent of the votes respectively. On Sunday, 52.75 percent of the
more than seven million registered voters went to the polls.
(Yugoslavia-Election)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- Chairman of the Myanmar State Peace and Development
Council and Prime Minister Senior-General Than Shwe will attend
the Second ASEAN Informal Summit scheduled to open on December 14
in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, an official announcement said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time for the Myanmar top leader to attend
a summit meeting of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) since it was admitted into the grouping in July along with
Laos. (Myanmar-ASEAN) 
</P>
</TEXT>
