<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 07:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Meet Pakistani PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Iranian supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei received Pakistani Prime Minister Mian
Nawaz Sharif Tuesday, underlining the importance of bilateral
ties, the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported today.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei said that the difficulties between Iran and Pakistan
were resolvable, stressing the need for further bolstering
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that there were traces of mysterious and dangerous
hands involved, whose objective is to disstabilize the relations
between Islamabad and Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The terrorist activities against Iranian interests in Pakistan
were the direct outcome of those perilous hands, he said,
expressing hope that the Pakistani government should take measures
to punish those involved in killing five Iranian military
technicians in Pakistan last September.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the situation in Afghanistan, the Iranian
supreme leader said that the current Afghan crisis could be
solved with the establishment of a broad-based government
acceptable to all the people of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He said that both Pakistan and Iran can help Afghanistan form
such a broad-based government.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the Pakistani prime minister said that both
Iran and Pakistan have suffered severe setbacks due to
Afghanistan's crisis and unstable conditions.
</P>
<P>
No country in the region is more keen in resolving the Afghan
crisis than Iran and Pakistan, he said, adding that the two
neighboring nations could use their influence to get all the
Afghan groups at a conference.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the promotion of bilateral relations, but
expressed his concern over the ongoing terrorist activities in
his country.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that the Pakistani courts would soon be able to
dispense their justice over the criminals who killed five
Iranians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Effort Made to Avert Violence in Kenya's Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Electoral Commission
has set up a committee to monitor compliance with the electoral
code of conduct by political parties in the campaign for the
December 29 General Election, the Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the Commission Chairman Samuel Kivuitu as
saying Tuesday that "the commission condemns unreservedly all
acts of violence."
</P>
<P>
He said that the commission was saddened that some party
leaders had allegedly vowed to disrupt functions of other parties
by "disorderly behavior and thuggery".
</P>
<P>
The electoral code of conduct forbids thuggery and use of
abusive language against other candidates and political parties.
</P>
<P>
These leaders are violently and deliberately infringing this
code, said the commission chairman, adding that this cannot be
allowed to continue.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "offended parties may be encouraged to
respond in a similar manner, leading to further violence and in
the end to a national catastrophe."
</P>
<P>
The election official urged Kenyan police to take firm action
against the perpetrators of violence and encouraged all Kenyans
to report all acts of violence and offensive behavior by
political party leaders, candidates and their supporters to the
commission and the police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
