<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Resume Formal Peace Talks with NDF Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Solicitor General Silvestre
Bello said the government is ready to resume the formal peace
talks with the National Democratic Front (NDF) rebels, the
Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Bello said the government peace panel will meet today to come
out with plans and possibly leave for the Netherlands on December
11 for weekend discussions with the NDF peace panel, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
NDF leader Jose Ma. Sison was in exile in the Netherlands, so
the government and the NDF peace panels held peace talks there.
</P>
<P>
"If this weekend schedule is not possible, we will find ways to
leave on December 26 or 27, right after Christmas, to complete
discussions concerning human rights and international humanitarian
law before the end of the year," Bello said.
</P>
<P>
The government's decision to resume the disrupted talks came on
the heels of the release of a police officer and a military man
captured by the NDF in a series of military attacks against
government units.
</P>
<P>
The government peace panel withdrew from the formal talks early
in November to press for the release of the two officers.
</P>
<P>
From his base in the Netherlands, Sison told the Philippine
media that the release of the hostages would help "improve the
climate for the resumption of the peace negotiations."
</P>
<P>
Sison had also announced the NDF decision to declare a
ceasefire from December 22 this year to January 2 next year in
response to the 30-day unilateral ceasefire declared by President
Fidel Ramos during the Christmas and New Year holidays.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
