<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Underwater Yangtze Museum to Be Built </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- China is going to build a
museum, 40 meters under water, at Baiheliang (White Crane Ridge),
in Fuling of southwest China's Chongqing city, to protect
hydrological relics at the site.
</P>
<P>
Yu Weichao, curator of the Museum of Chinese History and an
official in charge of the protection of cultural relics in the
Three Gorges area, said that Chinese experts have worked out two
designs for the project, one is in the shape of a fish and the
other in the shape of a diamond.
</P>
<P>
Yu said more experts like the fish-shape design.
</P>
<P>
The 1,600-meter-long and 15-meter-wide natural rock ridge of
Baiheliang is located in the Yangtze River to the south of
Fuling. It was given the name because of white cranes that used to
stop on it in ancient times.
</P>
<P>
Carvings on the rock ridge include over 30,000 characters and
18 fish figurines providing evidence on the changes in water level
of the Yangtze River during a period from the Tang Dynasty
(618-907) to the early 20th century.
</P>
<P>
Investigations show that Baiheliang is 140 meters above sea
level, only two to three meters higher than the lowest water level
of the Yangtze River in normal years, but 30 meters lower in flood
seasons. Baiheliang will be submerged 175 meters deep when the
Three Gorges Project is completed, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The museum, to cost 300 million yuan (37.5 million US dollars),
will also contain other hydrological cultural relics in the Three
Gorges area.
</P>
<P>
According to the design, the museum will be in four parts: an
underwater hall protecting Baiheliang carvings, a cultural relics
exhibition hall on land, a passageway connecting the underwater
facilities with the river bank and a tower. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Triples in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus
in October surged 220 percent from a year earlier to 1,081.3
billion yen (about 8.3 billion dollars), the Finance Ministry said
today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the sharp increase to strong exports
aided by the weak yen against the U.S. dollar and weak imports.
</P>
<P>
Exports increased by 16.9 percent to 4,507.5 billion yen (about
34.8 billion dollars), while imports, in contrast, showed a
marginal growth of 0.7 percent to 3,299.7 billion yen (about 25.5
billion dollars), the ministry said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
In goods and services trading in October, Japan registered a
surplus of 651.9 billion yen (about five billion dollars),
compared with a deficit of 10.7 billion yen (about 82.5 million
dollars) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Japan's surplus in merchandise trade in October jumped by 96.8
percent to 1,277.8 billion yen (about 9.9 billion dollars), up for
the seventh straight month, following a 30.4 percent surge in the
previous month.
</P>
<P>
In service trade, including tourism, Japan posted a deficit of
625.9 billion yen (about 4.8 billion dollars), smaller than the
deficit of 660.1 billion yen (about 5.1 billion dollars) a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
The current account balance measures the flow of goods and
services as well as investment and other monetary transfers.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the future current account surpluses, Japanese
government officials reiterated the government's view that the
surplus is unlikely to continue rising sharply over a medium or
long term because of structural changes in the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
But private sector economists forecast that the surplus will
continue to expand due to favorable overseas economic conditions,
particularly in the United States and Europe, and the continued
weakness of the yen against the dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Move to Third on NBA's Career Scoring List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Michael Jordan advanced to
the third spot on the National Basketball Association's career
scoring list after accumulating 27,432 points in 13 seasons on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Jordan reached the milestone in the first quarter of the
Chicago Bulls' game against the New York Knicks, making a short
bank shot over Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
That basket gave Jordan 27,411 points in 13 seaons, two more
than Moses Malone had in 19 seasons.
</P>
<P>
The two players ahead of Jordan are Wilt Chamberlain (31,419
points in 14 season) and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar (38,387 in 20).
Jordan will end up in the No. 3 spot if he goes through with his
plan to retire after this season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
