<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Keep Away from Drugs: Students Are Warned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen City, China's first
special economic zone, is taking measures to keep its 250,000
primary and middle school students away from narcotics.
</P>
<P>
All primary and middle schools in this south China city
organized students to watch movies on drugs.
</P>
<P>
"Keep away from drugs and do not harm your beautiful life,"
says the narcotics control department and education bureau of
Shenzhen in a joint proposal.
</P>
<P>
The education bureau of Nanshan District also organized
discussions on the harms of drugs among teachers and students.
</P>
<P>
The China National Narcotics Control Commission and the State
Education Commission issued a circular this month, calling for
efforts to enhance education on drugs among students in primary
and middle schools and institutions of higher learning.
</P>
<P>
The circular pointed out that the anti-drug move is a serious
matter related to social stability and the future of the country,
and that halting the emergence of new drug addicts is a major task
listed in the country's development plan.
</P>
<P>
"To provide education on drugs among students and to keep them
away from drugs is an extremely important task that will help
prevent the spread of drugs," the circular says.
</P>
<P>
To echo the circular, Shenzhen proposed again that all primary
and middle school students should abide by laws and regulations on
narcotics control and never let drugs pollute their life and the
campus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
