<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qing Dynasty Tombs Considered for World Heritage List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 10 (Xinhua) -- China has recently filed
a formal application with the World Heritage Committee of UNESCO
for including the Eastern Imperial Tombs group of the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911) on the World Cultural Heritage List.
</P>
<P>
The Eastern Imperial Tombs group in north China's cultural
relic-rich province of Hebei is one of the two biggest groups of
imperial tombs built for the imperial families in the Qing
Dynasty, the last in China's feudal society, according to the
application filed by the Eastern Imperial Tombs Administration.
</P>
<P>
Rich in unique design and artistic taste, the tombs had reached
a peak as far as ancient Chinese architecture is concerned.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1950s, state and provincial governments have invested
substantial sums into the tombs' maintenance. The state allocated
20 million yuan for maintenance in 1991-1995 alone.
</P>
<P>
The architectures and 40 square kilometers around the tombs are
well preserved, according to Yin Qinglin, who is in charge of
protection and maintenance of the ancient buildings.
</P>
<P>
"The tombs' architecture make it a very important component of
world heritage," Yin said.
</P>
<P>
The tombs were among the first group of key relics to be put
under state protection in 1961, and was one of 58 historical sites
in the province on the list.
</P>
<P>
The World Heritage Committee -- under the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) --
annually considers candidates for the World Heritage list.
</P>
<P>
The cultural and natural sites which are considered of
outstanding significance and universal value will be placed on the
World Heritage list for international protection.
</P>
<P>
So far, 19 historical and natural sites in China are on the
list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
