<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Network Operates in China's Fieldwork Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- China has set up a network for
obtaining data and research in resources, environment and ecology,
turning China's fieldwork research from individual to group
efforts, according to an ongoing conference here.
</P>
<P>
Lu Yongxiang, president of the Chinese Academy of Sciences
(CAS) said at the Second Fieldwork Conference that the network
will enable scientists to attain or provide fundamental data more
quickly, more accurately and in a wider range. The network can
better serve economic growth as well as scientific and
technological research, he said.
</P>
<P>
Fieldwork serves as the foundation of scientific research
concerning resources, the environment, biology and agriculture, as
well as being an important means for promoting high-tech
applications, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
To date, China has established 112 fieldwork centers and
observatories, covering research into forestry, lakes, deserts and
geomagnetism.
</P>
<P>
The CAS spent nearly 26.3 million U.S. dollars, of which 20
million dollars are loans from the World Bank, in setting up a
research network for ecological systems and one for biological
diversity research and information management.
</P>
<P>
China's fieldwork has provided a scientific basis for
government policy and strong technological support for industrial
development, and directly serves economic growth. It has also led
to the establishment and development of a number of new subjects
and theories.  
</P>
</TEXT>
