<HEADLINE> Salary Cuts Sought for Thai MPs, Cabinet Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai's Democrat Party is seeking support from other parties to
cut the salaries of members of parliament and cabinet members to
reduce state spending.
</P>
<P>
The party is proposing a 10-30 percent salary cut.
</P>
<P>
Coalition party whips are now seeking backing from opposition
parties.
</P>
<P>
Thai MPs earn 77,000 baht (1,833 US dollars) a month and are
entitled to employ up to five assistants, each at a stipend of
7,000 baht (167 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The number of assistants might be cut to three, and the 500
baht (12 dollars) meeting allowance could also be cut.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet members' salaries will be slashed by the same extent as
that of the MPs, if parliament endorses the move.
</P>
<P>
Democrat Party sources said that if the proposal is approved by
parliament, the salary reductions would become a "new year gift"
to the country from politicians.  
