<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks Reducing Business in Asia: Thai Vice PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Thai Deputy Prime Minister
Supachai Panitchpakdi has stated that foreign banks, particularly
those from the United States and Japan, were reducing their
business in Asia as they deem it "a risky region".
</P>
<P>
He said that although American and Japanese banks are reducing
their exposure in Asia for different reasons, the result would be
the same: loans to Thai companies would be recalled, putting
further pressure on the Thai currency, today's Bangkok Post quoted
him as saying on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said American banks due to close their books on
December 31 would have to reduce high-risk loans, mostly likely to
Asian companies, while Japanese banks are under pressure to boost
reserves to cover an increase in non-performing loans, but
domestic economic problems meant they are unlikely to be able to
raise the capital required.
</P>
<P>
To ease their burden, the Japanese banks will likely reduce
lending to other Asian countries. Recalling of loans will likely
start in January to improve the books before they close on March
31, according to Supachai, who is a well-known economic
specialist.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the reduction in exposure would be steady, as
central banks worldwide have advised their commercial counterparts
to reduce lending to Asia because it is considered "a risky
region". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
