<HEADLINE> Panamanians Demand More Payment for Victims of Invasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Panamanians are demanding
the government provide compensation to the relatives of civilian
victims of the 1989 U.S. invasion.
</P>
<P>
Clara Pitty, sister of Heriberto Pitty, one of the victims,
told the press Tuesday that the Panamanian government has not
compensated fairly those who lost their relatives during the
military raid.
</P>
<P>
She said that at the international level, no humanitarian
institution nor government has managed to bring justice to the
thousands of innocent victims.
</P>
<P>
"Our relatives died, some of them while at home, and others in
their work places, as my brother did, at the airport of Tocumen,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Evelia Diaz, who lost her husband Pablo Roberto Diaz, said that
nobody has helped her nor her 12 children.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Government and Justice Raul Montenegro recently
granted 144,880 U.S. dollars to relatives of soldiers killed
during the invasion.
</P>
<P>
Pitty is demanding the Panamanian government pay the same to
relatives of civilian victims.
</P>
<P>
The Catholic Church estimates that some 560 people died during
the invasion, most of them civilians trapped by cross-fire.
</P>
<P>
Humanitarian organizations and the ruling Democratic
Revolutionary Party say the death toll exceeds 2,000. 
</P>
