<HEADLINE> IMF to Lend More to Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund has cleared the way for lending Thailand another 2 billion US
dollars before February from the international rescue package,
according to local news reports today.
</P>
<P>
The approval in Washington on Monday indicates the IMF Board's
confidence in Thailand's economic program.
</P>
<P>
IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus said in a statement that
Thailand had made solid progress in implementing the IMF-supported
economic program, especially in the key area of restructuring the
financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Of the 2 billion dollars, 800 million dollars will be made
available to Thailand from the IMF this month.
</P>
<P>
A further 800 million dollars will come from Japan and 400-500
million dollars from central banks in the region before Thailand's
progress is next assessed in February.
</P>
<P>
The IMF-arranged international rescue package totaled 17.2
billion dollars to help Thailand overcome economic problems caused
by the collapse of the baht and mismanagement of the finance
sector.  
