<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Cuts Legal Oil Reserves to Save Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet on Tuesday
approved a cut in legal petroleum reserves in a move to ease
liquidity problems, save foreign exchange and reduce the cost of
oil products.
</P>
<P>
Domestic refiners and traders can reduce their reserves of
crude and refined oil products from 5 percent to 3 percent,
according to a Government House press release available today.
</P>
<P>
Importers of finished oil products can cut their reserves of
petrol and kerosene and jet fuel JP-1 from 10 percent to 6 percent
and trim reserves of diesel, fuel oil and crude from 5 percent to
3 percent, said the press release.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that the cut, which became effective on Tuesday,
would help reduce imports of crude and finished oil products and
save around 236 million dollars in foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
The reserve drop will also help lower oil costs, leading to a
reduction in retail prices of petrol, kerosene, diesel and fuel
oil.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's oil imports next year is estimated at 200 billion
baht (4.76 billion U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
