<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Distributes Anti-Poverty Loans to Rural Families </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Li Xinzhi used her 1,000-yuan
poverty alleviation loan obtained from the local government to buy
a buffalo and two sacks of chemical fertilizer for growing grain.
</P>
<P>
Li must repay 40 yuan each month on the loan she received in
June. She plans to sell hens from her farm to own the buffalo
outright by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
An ordinary woman from Cuihua Township, Li is one of many rural
residents receiving anti-poverty loans in Yi-Miao Autonomous
County of Luquan of southwest China's Yunnan Province. Her saying
of "using hens in exchange for a buffalo" is a popular poverty
alleviation method called "small credit" now being tried in rural
areas of Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
Under this plan, small interest-free loans are made directly to
an impoverished rural household.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, Yunnan Province has
implemented the plan with more than 7,000 rural households in 25
townships, issuing loans exceeding 6 million yuan. All the loans
have been repaid within the required time, and rural residents
have improved their living standards.
</P>
<P>
State Councillor Chen Junsheng, head of the Aid-the-Poor
Office, spoke highly of this practice during a recent inspection
tour of this southwestern Chinese province. Chen called for
expanding the plan to more rural areas of China.
</P>
<P>
During past decades, the Chinese government at central and
local levels have earmarked increased amount of money for
anti-poverty work. The efforts have begun to pay off. China's poor
population has decreased to 58 million from 250 million in 1978.
</P>
<P>
In the last two years alone, the small-loan plan has been used
for 15 projects in the country's 12 provinces and autonomous
regions where many of the country's poor are concentrated.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan, where many ethnic groups reside, has been known for its
arduous efforts to combat poverty.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xueren, a provincial official in charge of poverty
alleviation in Yunnan, said the small-loan method gives poor
families both motivation and pressure to use their initiative and
hard work to rise above the poverty line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
