<HEADLINE> Plane Crash Kills Three in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A commuter plane crashed in
central Canada today, killing three people and injuring 14 others,
television reports here said.
</P>
<P>
The plane crashed about 100 meters off the end of the runway at
about 3:30 p.m. local time while trying to land in "icy, misty"
weather.
</P>
<P>
There were two pilots and 15 passengers on board when the
accident happened.
</P>
<P>
Three of the survivors were critically injured and are waiting
to be flown out of the small community, about 300 kilometers
northeast of Winnipeg, capital of Manitoba province.
</P>
<P>
Two military aircraft and a helicopter were sent to the crash
site.
</P>
<P>
Bad weather had prevented the planes from leaving the community
called Little Grand Rapids.
</P>
<P>
Two companies had previously canceled flights into the region
because of bad weather.
</P>
<P>
The plane that crashed was an EMB 110, a twin-engine turb-prop
regional commuter aircraft with a capacity of 19 people. It was
built in 1982 by Brazil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
