<HEADLINE> Voters Disillusioned In Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A national study shows that
the intended turnout for next year's general elections in Costa
Rica is very low.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by the National University's Institute of
Social Studies on Population, said the intention to vote had
reduced from 58 to 56 percent of registered voters.
</P>
<P>
The main causes for the disappointment are the unfulfillment of
previous promises, the deception of politicians, and
dissatisfaction with the candidates.
</P>
<P>
Slightly above two million Costa Ricans are registered voters
for the elections which are scheduled for next February.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen candidates are competing for the presidency, but just
two of them -- the Social Christian Miguel Angel Rodriguez and the
Social Democrat Jose Miguel Corrales -- have a chance of winning.
</P>
