<HEADLINE> Beijing Enterprises Urged to Improve Management, Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- A large electrical equipment
producer was held up by the Beijing government recently as an
example for failing industrial enterprises to emulate.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Switches Factory, like thousands of state enterprises,
suffered from the "big enterprise syndrome" -- industrial giants
with long histories, redundant workers, a large number of retirees
and an inflexible management system unable to adapt in a changing
market. In 1991, Beijing Switches Factory was on the edge of
bankruptcy with a loss of 4 million yuan in 1991.
</P>
<P>
"It was not for me to write the last chapter of the factory,"
said Huang Guocheng, director of the factory. To improve the
management and train his staff, Huang formulated a slogan:
99+1=0. Huang said it meant that a single poor product or one
quality-check error could cancel out all the positive results. "I
apply the slogan to all the enterprise's work flow," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Strict management has made Beijing Switches Factory the market
leader among China's electrical equipment producers. In terms of
economic return, the enterprise last year paid the state 27
million yuan in profit and taxes. "Nowadays, we don't owe a penny
in loans or taxes to the state," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
A marketable product, strict quality control, cost-efficient
management and a widespread post-sales service network are all
considered factors contributing to the factory's success. All
these factors are "applicable to other state enterprises," said
Yang Anjiang, vice mayor of Beijing in charge of its industrial
sector.
</P>
<P>
After the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of
China, the Chinese government has introduced all possible means to
activate inert state-owned industries. These enterprises, still
the majority of China's industry, were also urged to improve
quality control and overall management to become more
cost-efficient. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
