<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reports Constant Financial Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- China's financial sector has
been stable this year in sharp contrast to global financial
turbulence, particularly in Southeast Asia, "China Securities"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Appropriate growth in the money supply and improvement in the
structure of the loan portfolio are important symbols of stability
in China, the daily financial newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the People's Bank of China, the central bank,
show that the outstanding value of M2, which is the combination of
cash in circulation plus all sorts of deposits, was up 17.1
percent in the first three quarters from last year. The growth
rate was 8.2 percent down from last year's figure.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding amount of M1, which is the combination of cash
in circulation plus demand deposits of enterprises, grew 17.3
percent between January and September, during which the M0, or the
value of cash in circulation, rose 12.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
All three indices were near or approaching the Chinese
government's target for financial macro-control for 1997.
</P>
<P>
On the foreign exchange market, the Chinese yuan has been
stable throughout the year, with its exchange rate slightly
consolidated against a group of Western currencies led by the
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
In terms of foreign exchange, China has the second largest
amount with 134.07 billion U.S. dollars at the end of September,
up 29 billion U.S. dollars from the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
China has also been successful in enhancing supervision and
preventing and eliminating risks this year, which is named the
"Year of Preventing Financial Risks."
</P>
<P>
For instance, the outstanding value of debts involved in bond
re-purchases plunged from the previous 70 billion yuan to 16.5
billion yuan at the end of July, down 76 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Overall and systematic debt risks have been basically
eradicated," "China Securities" declared.
</P>
<P>
Also this year China increased its financial support for
reforming state-owned enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
