<HEADLINE> Shanghai Customs Uncovers Smuggled Cultural Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Customs officers in Shanghai
have recently crushed a smuggling case involving 130 pieces of
precious Chinese cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
The relics were found in four parcels mailed by a Japanese
tourist from a local express mail service company. He claimed
these relics as "bowls" in the customs declaration forms.
</P>
<P>
Inspections by experts found that 64 pieces are cultural relics
that strictly banned by the state from being taken out of the
country. They include a blue porcelain dish dating some 3,000
years back, a 2,400-year old pottery jar and lots of articles from
Dynasties of Han, Song and Ming, with 350 years of history at
the least.
</P>
<P>
The rest 66 pieces belong to modern China. Such relics should
gain the state permission before they are taken out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Customs and cultural relics protection authorities in Shanghai
have called for reinforced efforts to stop relics smuggling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
