<HEADLINE> China Tries to Exhibit Cultural Treasures Globally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- China is making greater
efforts to present its long and eventful history to foreigner in a
more interesting and attractive way, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
About 100 officials from provincial cultural relics bureaux
have gathered in Beijing to explore ways to display more of
China's cultural treasure trove abroad. The three-day meeting
opened Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The world is probably now experiencing its most fervent "China
craze" since Marco Polo wrote about his travels in China. This
wave has been given momentum by the increasing number of cultural
relics being allowed abroad for display in exhibitions or being
introduced to the world through a variety of other channels.
</P>
<P>
In the last five years, China has held more than 150
exhibitions abroad. Several large exhibitions such as "Treasures
from Tibet of the People's Republic of China," "The Civilization
of the Yellow River," and "Ancient China" have attracted millions
of foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
One of the direct results of such international exchanges is
that international organizations have paid more attention to the
protection of relics in China. Since 1992, China has received more
than 20 million US dollars in financial aid form abroad.
</P>
<P>
"New technologies and money from abroad have helped to protect
cultural relics in a more scientific and efficient way, and to
train the personnel involved in protection work," said Zhang
Wenbin, director of the State Bureau of Cultural Relics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
