<HEADLINE> Serbians to Vote Again for President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A second round of presidential
elections will be held on December 21, the Serbian Election
Committee announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the final results released by the committee, none
of the seven candidates won the threshold 50 percent of the votes
in the first round of election held on December 7.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, 52.75 percent of the more than seven million
registered voters went to the polls.
</P>
<P>
Serbian Foreign Minister Milan Milutinovic, of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic's ruling Socialist Party, and
Vojislav Seseji of the Radical Party took the lead, pocketing 43.7
percent and 32.19 percent of the votes respectively.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the election held on December 7, Serbian voters cast
their ballots twice before, on September 21 and October 5, none of
which produced valid results.
</P>
<P>
In comparison with the preceding ones, two changes were
discerned with this election. One was that about five percent
fewer voters participated than the first round of elections.
</P>
<P>
Another was that Milutinovic topped Seseji in the new voting,
while Seseji took the lead in the election on October 5. 
</P>
