<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze Source Faces Environmental Menace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The ecological environment at
the source of the Yangtze River, China's longest river, faces
great peril from human activities, with pasturelands receding,
rare animals species on the verge of extinction and the
evolutionary chain of living beings facing great damage.
</P>
<P>
The aforementioned conclusions were reached by an inspection
team organized by the China Environmental Protection Foundation.
The team reached its conclusions following an on-site
investigation and analysis of the ecological environment, water
quality and flow capacity of three major rivers at the source of
the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The source area of the Yangtze, located on the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau, a region widely knowq as the "Roof of the World", covers
140,000 sq.km. severely lacking in vegetation due to the high
elevation, low temperatures and poor soil conditions.
</P>
<P>
Experts on the team have called on relevant departments to
draft a comprehensive plan to protect the ecological environment
in the source area of the Yangtze. They have also called for
strict controls on activities such as grazing, hunting, tourism
and economic exploitation.
</P>
<P>
The team's recent report also pointed to the good water quality
and relatively good air quality in the source area.
</P>
<P>
The team of 14 experts, scholars and personnel from seven
institutes, as well as two experts from Japan, completed the
inspection over an 18-day period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
