<HEADLINE> Rallies Support Civil Rights Nominee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Bill Lann Lee's supporters
rallied in several cities Tuesday for a Senate vote on his stalled
nomination to be the assistant attorney general for civil rights.
</P>
<P>
Supporters hoped these events in major cities would help
pressure Republicans to schedule a vote on Lee, a career civil
rights lawyer whose nomination the Senate Judiciary Committee
failed to clear so far.
</P>
<P>
But a spokeswoman for Senate Republican Leader Trent Lott said
a vote was unlikely because Lott also opposes Lee.
</P>
<P>
Asian-American and civil rights groups rallied in several
cities including Los Angeles, New York, Detroit and Cleveland to
drum up support for Lee, 48, a son of Chinese immigrants, the
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Democratic senators also scheduled radio interviews.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday was the 40th anniversary of the civil rights division,
which has been without a permanent head since January.
</P>
<P>
"Enough is enough. The civil rights position has been vacant
too long," Representative Maxine Waters, a Democrat, who chairs
the Congressional Black Caucus, said at a rally at the Asian
Pacific Legal Center in her Los Angeles district.
</P>
<P>
Clinton issued a statement saying he nominated Lee because the
job of "fulfilling the promise of our civil rights laws... is far
from over."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "Bill Lann Lee deserves to be America's next
assistant attorney general for civil rights."
</P>
<P>
The coast-to-coast events and Lee's appearances in Washington
Monday and Tuesday are part of a campaign to force the Senate to
act.
</P>
<P>
But Senate critics, led by the Judiciary Committee chairman,
Senator Orrin Hatch, a Republican, say Lee's support of
affirmative action makes him unfit for the job of protecting all
Americans from bias.
</P>
<P>
Lee is the Western regional counsel for the NAACP Legal Defense
and Educational Fund. 
</P>
