<HEADLINE> World Chess Championship Opens in Netherlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Higher-ranked players
dominated the first day's matches when the FIDE World Chess
Championship, which drew some 68 grandmasters and masters, opened
in Groningen, Netherlands on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The only exception was Hungarian Peter Leko, who ranked 2635,
lost to German Roman Slobodan (2550) but no one was eliminated on
the first day because of the two-game format, with players
exchanging white and black for the return game Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 28 of the top players would enter the second round
directly on Thursday after receiving first-round byes.
</P>
<P>
