<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Minister: Latin America Ready for FTAA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Commerce
Minister Jose Manuel Salazar said Tuesday that Latin America is
ready to set up the Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA) by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Salazar made the remarks in Miami, the United States, where he
is participating the 21st Conference on Latin America and the
Caribbean attended by 650 businessmen and officials.
</P>
<P>
The FTAA was proposed by U.S. President Bill Clinton to the
heads of states of the 34 hemispheric countries in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
Extensive negotiations on the FTAA will start in 1998 at the
western hemisphere summit in Santiago, Chile.
</P>
<P>
Salazar gave assurance that at the summit, the Latin American
leaders will release a final document and will define the
negotiating goals, terms, structure and role of ministers when the
FTAA is established.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that there will be negotiations about special
treatment for small economies, as well as environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
Doubts about the negotiations have emerged as the U.S.
Congress denied Clinton authorization to negotiate the FTAA
establishment through "the fast track."
</P>
<P>
The fast track is a commitment by the U.S. Congress to accept
without change agreements the president negotiates with other
nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Tourism Industry Revenue Up in Summer 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian revenue from tourism in
the summer of 1997 was 10 percent up from the same period of 1996,
Deputy Trade and Tourism Minister Mariyana Assenova told a
national tourism conference here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He contributed this partly to the arrest of a three-year
downward tendency in foreign visitors arrivals. The number of
tourists went up by eight to ten percent from 1996, of them, the
Germans accounted for 41 percent, Assenova said.
</P>
<P>
Tourism once generated some 9.4 percent of Bulgaria's gross
domestic product and offered 8.6 percent of job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
In order to further promote the tourism market, Assenova said,
a Tourism Act will be worked out to provide new regulations for
licensing and awarding star rating to tourism companies in
addition to an inventory of facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
