<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhou Enlai's Hometown Builds Museum in His Honor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The late Premier Zhou Enlai's
hometown, Shaoxing in east China's Zhejiang Province, has
built a museum for Zhou, who was one of the founders of the new
China.
</P>
<P>
The museum, covering an area of 2,150 square meters, is
scheduled to open to the public on March 5, 1998, the 100th
anniversary of Zhou's birth.
</P>
<P>
A white marble statue of Zhou in martial attire stands at the
middle of the museum. The east hall exhibit is dedicated to the
close relationship between Zhou and his hometown. The west hall
contains photos of Zhou's life, according to the designer
of the museum.
</P>
<P>
The ancient-style museum is based on the former residence of
Zhou, in which Zhou's father and grandfather had lived for years.
When Zhou participated in the Chinese revolution, he returned
often to his hometown. In March of 1939, Zhou came back to sweep
the ancestral tombs and to propagate the idea of resisting
Japanese aggression.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Zhou's former residence has become a base for
patriotic education. Chinese leaders such as Jiang Zemin and Li
Peng have visited the site. In March this year, local governments
decided to renovate the residence and build a new museum.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 60 items left by Zhou and his wife, Deng
Yingchao, have been collected, as well as 20 letters and documents
and more than 100 photos.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
