<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine banks posted growth
in the third quarter of this year despite the volatile financial
markets in Southeast Asia, the Business Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted data from the Central Bank as saying that
the assets of 52 commercial banks operating in the country reached
2.366 trillion pesos (about 67.6 billion U.S. dollars), up 4.3
percent from the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
Loans grew up to 1.477 trillion pesos (42.2 billion dollars),
up by 5.5 percent from the previous quarter and 34.6 percent from
the year-ago level.
</P>
<P>
In the first three quarters of this year, investment accounts
surged to 369.2 billion pesos (10.5 billion dollars) while
deposits expanded to 1.4 trillion pesos (40 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank said the capital adequacy of local banks
remained high with a risk asset ratio of 16.5 percent as of
October, indicating that the country's commercial banks "remained
healthy" in the financial crisis sweeping much of Asia.
</P>
<P>
However, a senior official of the Department of Finance warned
that the banks' current stability was being threatened by soaring
interest rates which were forcing borrowers to take in huge
losses.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Finance is considering allowing more foreign
banks to enter the country to lower the "artificially high"
interest rates, but the Central Bank and the Bankers Association
of the Philippines oppose the proposal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
