<HEADLINE> Italy's 1998 Budget Awaits Approval From Lower House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government's 1998
budget is awaiting final approval from the lower house today with
a key chapter on pension reforms undecided and the opposition
promising to end tax hikes.
</P>
<P>
Though Budget Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi urged the lower
house to pass the budget quickly, a dispute over the pensions for
the self-employed and the opposition's filibuster could hold the
budget from approval by the parliament till next year, reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Ciampi said that if approval of the budget does not meet the
December 21 deadline, Italy's chances of qualifying for the
European single currency would be seriously jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
Lower House Speaker Luciano Violante also called for a speedy
approval of the budget bill. He suggested, however, the government
listened "carefully to the questions raised by the opposition."
</P>
<P>
The opposition Freedom Front has recently staged a marathon
filibuster in the lower house to block the approval of government
measures to raise VAT rates.
</P>
<P>
The main obstacles to budget approval are a series of proposed
changes to the pension system for the self-employed, which were
put forward by the center-right Freedom Front last week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Romano Prodi is reportedly meeting
his finance, treasury and labor ministers today for a solution to
the issue of self-employed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
