<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Rupiah Falls To Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah fell to
4,600/4,630 against the U.S. dollar Tuesday afternoon from an
opening of 4,145, losing 11 percent in a singly day -- the
sharpest fall since Indonesia abandoned fixed exchange rates in
1971.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has already fallen by 94 percent since January when
it stood at 2,363 to the U.S. dollar, and was down 91 percent
since the government floated the currency on August 14.
</P>
<P>
"This is crazy. The rupiah is just like jumping from a plane
without a parachute," a dealer with a local bank said.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the free fall of the rupiah was driven by market
rumors that President Soeharto was suffering a stroke. The rumor
was denied by State Secretary Moerdiono later in the day.
</P>
<P>
"Emergency action is needed, otherwise the rupiah could go down
as low as 5,000 against the U.S. dollar. What is happening now is
beyond imagination. Now every hour we see a new low," a market
analyst with a joint venture bank said.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said that drastic policies such as capital
controls may be taken, but there would be a cost for such a move.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
