<HEADLINE> Ramos Explains Choice of Ruling Party's Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos said House of Representatives Speaker Jose de Venecia's
better winning chance in the 1998 presidential elections prompted
him to anoint de Venecia as the ruling party's presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
Ramos defended his choice of de Venecia over former Defense
chief Renato de Villa on Tuesday, saying the choice was not based
on loyalty but on many factors, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We based our party decision on many factors and the most
important one is the winnability of the Lakas (ruling party)
ticket from top to bottom," Ramos was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Ramos said, he based his endorsement on the results
of a survey conducted among congressmen, city mayors, provincial
governors, district chairmen and other party leaders.
</P>
<P>
Ramos anointed de Venecia, who won widespread support of a
large contingent of congressmen and their constituencies, as the
Lakas-NUCD ruling party's presidential bet in the 1998 polls.
</P>
<P>
For his part, de Venecia said his running mate will be
announced in a week after consultations with President Ramos and
other party leaders. He said Vice President Joseph Estrada will be
his most formidable rival in next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
On his platform, de Venecia said he would continue the
successful economic reforms and modernization efforts initiated by
the Ramos administration.  
</P>
