<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Says No to Proposed European Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Greece today expressed its
opposition to the holding of an European conference which is to be
attended by the 15 member states of the European Union (EU), 11
prospective members and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in parliament tonight, Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis said that his country considered it unnecessary because
the content of the conference was unclear and issues for
discussion had not been determined.
</P>
<P>
Regarding Turkey's participation in the conference, Simitis
said that Turkey could attend the conference under three
conditions, namely the jurisdiction of the international court at
the Hague, the unimpeded course of Cyprus toward EU accession, and
progress in the talks for solving the Cyprus issue on the basis of
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Greece was in favor of a simultaneous start
to negotiations with all 11 prospective members.
</P>
<P>
As for the economic cost of EU expansion, Simitis said that
Athens would put up a strong fight so that along with the other
countries of the south, it would not lose resources from the
structural funds, and so that the third community support
framework would provide the necessary credits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At least 50 Injured as Two German Trains Collide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- At least 50 people were injured, 14 of
them seriously, when a local passenger train and a fuel-loaded freight
train collided head-on near the northern German city of Hannover late
this afternoon, said latest reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The police and the rail authorities have differed in their casualty
count, with the police saying that at least 64 people were injured,
compared with 50 reported by the rail authorities.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses said that three of the freight train's 22 tank wagons
burst into flame after the crash at about 16:50 local time, but
firefighters had managed to put out the fire before it reached a
fourth wagon.
</P>
<P>
The engine and three wagons of the passenger train were derailed in
the accident with its driver seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that many of the 300 passengers were wandering about
the remote accident area in panic. About 400 policemen and
firefighters had been involved in the rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
Hospitals in the area were standing on alert to admit a large
number of casualties. All ambulances available nearby had been sent to
the scene.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities said they had to wait until Wednesday to clarify
the cause of the crash. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Dollar Falls Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell against
the Japanese yen today on the potentially good news that the
Japanese government would take measures to pull the economy out of
its financial troubles.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar changed hands at 129.59
yen, down from 130.45 late Monday. The dollar also settled at
1.7904 marks, up from 1.7893, its highest level since September 23
when it reached 1.8010.
</P>
<P>
There were reports that the Japanese government might announce
details of a financial stabilization package Wednesday. And Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto was considering selling 10 trillion yen
worth of bonds to assist the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday:
1.4528 Swiss francs, down from 1.4579; 5.9902 French francs, up
from 5.9863; 1,751 Italian lire, down from 1,752; and 1.4200
Canadian dollars, down from 1.4231.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6507 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6483 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
