<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Obtains Two World Bank Credits for Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today okayed
a 25 million U.S. dollar credit for Albania's economic
rehabilitation program and a 5 million dollar equivalent as
technical assistance for its recovery program.
</P>
<P>
The rehabilitation credit will provide financial support for
the first stage in the Albanian government's economic recovery
program. The second credit will provide assistance to implement
the government's program in such key areas as the financial
sector, public sector management, public administration and
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
The rehabilitation credit will address two key issues:
structural weaknesses in the economy that have caused the recent
crisis, and the strengthening of the social safety net through the
alleviation of poverty and unemployment created by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The credits will be channeled through the International
Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessionary
lending arm for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
After Albania joined the IDA in 1993, IDA commitments to the
country total some 273 million dollars for 20 projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census Bureau Figures Show Asian-Americans Younger, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Asian-Americans tend to be
younger and better educated than other Americans, and they're more
likely to live in cities and less likely to be divorced, according
to Census Bureau figures released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The profile of the nation's 9,653,000 Asians and Pacific
Islanders, or 3.7 percent of the population, was based on the
March 1996 Current Population Survey.
</P>
<P>
Asians are concentrated in the West, with 55 percent living in
that part of the country, and 94 percent of Asian-Americans live
in metropolitan areas, compared with 80 percent of the total
population, according to the Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The median age of Asians and Pacific Islanders is 29.8 years,
while The nation's median age is 33.9 years, the figures show.
Median means half of the people are older and half younger than
that age.
</P>
<P>
Only 3.8 percent of Asians are currently divorced, compared
with 8.9 percent of all Americans at age of 15 and over. About
the same share is currently married and living with their spouse
-- 53.5 percent for Asians and 53.4 percent overall -- but more
Asians have never married, 34.8 percent compared with 27.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
For people age 25 and over, 41.7 percent of Asians have a
college degree, compared with 23.6 percent of the general
population, said the Bureau report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
