<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Supports Turkey's Bid to Join EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said here today that Britain supports Turkey's bid to join
the European Union (EU) and Turkey should be included in the
European Conference of EU membership hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz this evening, Blair reaffirmed Britain's backing for "an
increasingly close relationship between Turkey and Western
institutions, notably the EU."
</P>
<P>
Blair stressed that Britain, due to take over the rotating EU
presidency, wanted Turkey's EU membership application to be
"judged by the same criteria as those of other applicants."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yilmaz told Blair that Turkey's bid to join the EU
should not be discriminated against.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Labor government has proposed a European Conference
should be established early next year to ensure that a close
dialogue is maintained between the EU and those countries which
are not invited in the next wave of EU enlargement.
</P>
<P>
EU leaders are expected to make a final decision concerning the
conference later this week at the EU summit in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 15-nation bloc members agreed to include Turkey in
the European Conference, but Greece and Germany have expressed
opposition to Turkey's inclusion in the conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
