<HEADLINE> US Indicates Willingness for Dialogue With Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
renewed a call for dialogue with Iran after Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami suggested a dialogue with the West.
</P>
<P>
"We've long been open to a dialogue with the Iranian
government," State Department spokesman James Foley told reporters
at a regular briefing. "Our only stipulation has been that such a
dialogue take place with an authorized representative of the
government and that it be acknowledged publicly."
</P>
<P>
He was responding to Khatami's speech at the Organization of
the Islamic Conference summit in Tehran today.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, suggesting the time for a dialogue with the West has
come, said, "Our era is an era of preponderance of the Western
culture and civilization, whose understanding is imperative."
</P>
<P>
Foley said the United States would "welcome and support the
idea of an open dialogue between different cultures and
civilization."
</P>
<P>
Foley also said the United States had "no quarrel with the
Iranian people" and was "not seeking to change the nature" of
Iran's Islamic government.
</P>
<P>
Foley denied his remarks constituted a policy shift but
observers here said the remarks reflected an important change of
emphasis.
</P>
<P>
"We're coming out on the side of dialogue and also," said
Richard Murphy, a former assistant secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
Some other observers here said Foley's remarks came at a time
when the Clinton administration is feeling left out in the cold
while many of its closest Arab allies, including senior officials
from Egypt and Saudi Arabia, are in Tehran for the summit of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
