<HEADLINE> Iranian, Syrian Leaders Call for Islamic Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei today met Syrian President Hafez Al-Assad, saying it
is time for the Islamic world to rally against Israel and its
supporter, the United States.
</P>
<P>
During the hour-long meeting with the staunch supporter of
Iran in its 1980-88 war with Iraq, Khamenei said the frustration
over the U.S. policy of unconditional support for Israel is widely
felt in most Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
This has become a rallying point for Muslim states, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the victory of Islamic Revolution in 1979, Iran has
declared Israel an enemy, calling it a usurper Zionist regime and
opposing any peace-making with it.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei said Syria, which lost its Golan Heights to Israel in
the 1967 war, is the "pivot of anti-Zionist struggles
and a frontline country in the campaign against" Israel.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad called on Khamenei on the sidelines of the ongoing
summit of the Organization of the Islamic Conference, which is
attended by most of its 55 member nations. This is his
first participation in the OIC meeting.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei expressed the hope that Iran's hosting of the summit
would offer a "good opportunity to tap potential in the Muslim
world for confronting" Israel and guaranteeing Islamic interests.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian president said that selecting Tehran as the
venue raised hopes of success of the summit, adding this is
the reason for his first presence at an OIC summit.
</P>
<P>
In the face of closer military cooperation between Israel
and Turkey, Iran and Syria have tried to join hands to
counter the possible threat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
