<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Seeking Changes of Fuel System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Boeing Company is
examing possible changes to fuel systems of the 747s after
investigators focused their attention on the system in probing the
explosion of a Trans World Airlines Boeing 747 that killed 230
people near New York in July last year.
</P>
<P>
The company's move was explained by Ivor Thomas, a fuel expert
of the company, at the second-day hearings on the accident at
Baltimore, Maryland, today. But Thomas said the company was
progressing carefully to make sure it did not introduce some new
safety problem.
</P>
<P>
The National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) tests this
Summer designed to replicate the flight of TWA 800 showed fuel in
one portion of the center tank reaching 145 degrees Fahrenheit
(62.7 C), well above the 100 degrees the industry sets as a lower
limit.
</P>
<P>
Based on the tests, the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration
(FAA) on November 26 asked airlines to install new equipment to
shield certain wiring in the fuel monitoring system in some Boeing
747s and called for immediately inspections on wiring in some fuel
pumps in older Boeing 747s after the NTSB's tests.
</P>
<P>
At the hearings today, aviation industry representatives and
the FAA explained that the fuel tank vapors were always assumed to
be explosive so they had concentrated on eliminating ignition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Gives New Approach to Environmental Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Policy-makers and
investors should know the long-term benefits of investments in
environmental protection instead of chasing after the short-term
gains through conventional investments, a U.N. study showed.
</P>
<P>
Small changes in the way governments and investors look at
environmental resources can save billions of dollars, the study,
Valuing our Future: Cost-Benefit Analysis and Sustainability,
issued here today said.
</P>
<P>
The 47-page study said people tend to take a "utilitarian"
investment approach.
</P>
<P>
Author of the study Geoffrey Heal, professor of Economics and
Finance at Columbia University, depicted his point with an example
of New York City's water system.
</P>
<P>
The city has to invest its water purification plants, each
costing 6 to 8 billion U.S. dollars because damage to soil
ecosystems by pollution has reduced their ability to purify water
collected in reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
However, the purification "can be achieved by restoring the
ecological integrity of its watershed region at the cost of 1.2
billion dollars," Heal said, adding that "the economic value of an
environmental asset, a functioning watershed, is dramatically
illustrated by this case."
</P>
<P>
Introducing the study to the press, United Nations Development
Program officials said the study can help solve the problem of
balancing the interests of future generations with those of the
present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
