<HEADLINE> France Holds On to Its Candidate for Euro Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- French Finance Minister Dominique
Strauss-Kahn stressed here today that Paris sees no reason to back
down from its nomination of French central banker Jean-Claude
Trichet as a candidate to lead the future European central bank.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with his German counterpart, Theo
Waigel, in Bonn, Strauss-Kahn noted that every country had the
right to nominate its own candicate for the top post at the
European central bank. It was up to the EU government leaders to
make the final choice, he added.
</P>
<P>
The dispute over who will head the European central bank was
ignited last month when the French government surprisingly
announced that it wanted Trichet, governor of the Bank of France,
to take the job.
</P>
<P>
Most other EU countries, including Germany, had expected the
Dutch head of the European Monetary Institute, Wim Duisenberg, to
take the post.
</P>
<P>
According to Strauss-Kahn, there is no hurry to make a decision
on the leadership issue at next week's EU summit in Luxembourg. EU
states could take time to make the choice until next March, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
