<HEADLINE> Israel: Military Ties With Ankara Directed to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli-Turkish cooperation
is aimed at resisting regional military threats that target the
two countries, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai, who arrived here Monday on a three-day visit, was
quoted by Anatolia News Agency as saying these threats come from
some unstable countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
If a country supports terrorism and is also eager for access to
chemical and nuclear weapons, it can be deemed as threat,
Mordechai said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that the Israeli official is referring
to Syria and Iran although he failed to give specific names of the
countries.
</P>
<P>
However, Mordechai reiterated that Israeli's military
cooperation with Turkey is by no means directed at any other
countries.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the closer ties and cooperation between the
two countries will contribute to peace and stability in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Mordechai visited the Turkish Aerospace
Industries, a producer of Turkey's F-16 jets.
</P>
<P>
The increasing relations between Turkey and Israel have
triggered strong criticism from the Arab countries, which accused
Ankara of betraying the interests of the Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a predominantly Muslim but secular state, has said
that its move to develop military cooperation with Israel will
not produce negative impact on its friendship with the Arab
countries.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai is the first Israeli defense minister who pays
official visit to Turkey, according to Israeli Embassy in
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
