<HEADLINE> Adams to Urge UK Government to Leave N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- President of Sinn Fein, the
political wing of IRA, Gerry Adams, said today he would tell
British Prime Minister Tony Blair on Thursday to pull out of
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time since 1921, a British prime minister is
going to hear Irish republicans politely, but very firmly, tell
him that it's time to go, that it is time for Britain to end its
constitutional claim to a part of our country," local reports
quoted Adams as saying at a Sinn Fein meeting.
</P>
<P>
Adams is scheduled to meet with Blair on Thursday in Downing
Street No. 10, to become the first leader of Sinn Fein to have
such talks with British prime minister in London for 76 years.
</P>
<P>
In 1921, Northern Ireland republican leader Michael Collins
signed a treaty in London with prime minister David Lloyd George
that set up a Free State in most of the island of Ireland but left
six northern counties under British rule, a deal that sparked a
bloody Irish civil war.
</P>
<P>
Adams said the talks would be "another phase in the republican
struggle", adding that he wanted some idea of Blair's vision for
the future of Anglo-Irish relations.
</P>
<P>
"But let me assure you that when we meet Tony Blair in London
this week at the top of our agenda is a free, independent and
united Ireland," he said.
</P>
<P>
Irish Republican Army (IRA), which has been fighting to end the
British rule for the past 30 years, called a ceasefire in July,
which enabled Sinn Fein to have a seat at all-party talks on the
future of Northern Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
