<HEADLINE> Arab League Chief Hopes for Better Arab-Iran Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the Arab
League Ahmed Esmat Abdel Meguid today expressed his hope that Iran
will step up efforts to improve its relations with Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on the sidelines of the eighth summit of
the Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC), Meguid said that he
has felt a new approach by Iran and some Arab countries to improve
their ties.
</P>
<P>
"Iran is opening a new era with the Arab world," he said, "and
I believe Iran is keen to have good relations with Arab countries."
</P>
<P>
Tehran's relations with the Arab neighbors cooled down after
its Islamic Revolution in 1979. It has either territorial disputes
or religious divergences with them.
</P>
<P>
However, it launched a series of diplomatic initiatives this
year to better its relations with the Arab world, the Gulf
countries in particular.
</P>
<P>
Meguid said that the ongoing Islamic summit, which lasts from
Tuesday to Thursday, would serve the development of future
relations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the leader of the 22-member Arab body criticized
Turkey for striking military pacts with Israel, saying it would
have negative impact on the ties between Turkey and Arab
countries.
</P>
<P>
Meguid dismissed the accusation that Syria supports Turkey's
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in its separatist drive,
noting that the PKK issue is an internal affair of Turkey and has
nothing to do with any Arab country.
</P>
<P>
He ruled out the possibility that the Arab nations will take
unified actions against Turkey, saying the Arabs expect Ankara to
understand their concerns over its military cooperation with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Meguid announced his readiness to mediate between Turkey and
Arab states to remove misunderstandings and improve relations.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed opposition to any military actions by the
United States against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"As a superpower, the U.S. can maintain its forces in the
Persian Gulf region, and we are not afraid of it," he said.
</P>
<P>
But "we will oppose it if it wants to take any military action
against Iraq," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
