<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0355 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Tool for Detecting Space Storms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists said they
could predict space storms that threaten astronauts and satellites
in orbit and knock out power and communications systems on Earth
more accurately owing to a new instrument called coronograph
aboard the SOHO spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
The scientists presented their findings Monday at the fall
meeting of the American Geophysical Union in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
The instrument, jointly operated by NASA and the European Space
Agency, can block out the bright light of the Sun so as to allow
scientists to focus on the Sun's dimmer corona.
</P>
<P>
With this new tool, scientists detected nine giant solar
eruptions, called coronal mass ejections, that threw big chunks of
the Sun's atmosphere toward Earth between December 1996 and June
1997.
</P>
<P>
All the nine giant solar eruptions of positively charged
particles caused magnetic storms on Earth, and one of them,
observed on January 10, had permanently knocked out the major
communications satellite Telstar 401.
</P>
<P>
Scientists had in the past to derive their predictions of
magnetic storms from observing solar flares, but the coronal mass
ejections detected by SOHO can occur with no flares or only weak
flares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971210.0356 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Inflation Rate Remains Above Gov't Target in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Britain's underlying annual rate
of inflation was unchanged at 2.8 percent last month, causing the
government to miss its 2.5 percent target for its seventh month in
power, showed official figures today.
</P>
<P>
Figures released today by the Office for National Statistics
showed that the headline rate of inflation at 3.7 percent in
November was also unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The figures were largely in line with economists' expectations.
Most analysts had expected the underlying rate, which excludes
mortgage interest payments, to fall to 2.7 percent while the
headline rate had been forecast to pose a modest rise.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the figures indicated that the Bank of
England would probably raise the interest rate again in order to
meet its inflation target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
