<HEADLINE> Blair Pledges "New Lease of Life" for NHS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair pledged today he would give the National Health Service
(NHS) "a new lease of life."
</P>
<P>
"I will take on those who say that the NHS has had its day and
that all we can do is preside over its slow decline," he said.
</P>
<P>
A 10-year plan for health reforms is due to be set out in a
government White Paper. These are expected to include abolishing
the NHS internal market, saving 1 billion pounds (1.7 billion U.S.
dollars) by cutting red tape, reducing the number of NHS trusts
and health authorities.
</P>
<P>
"I have great ambitions for the NHS, not just muddling through
or coping but taking a bold and positive leap forward," the prime
minister said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government had already allocated 1.5 billion
pounds (2.5 billion U.S. dollars) for the NHS this year and next,
with more money for tackling breast cancer,improving children's
services and building new hospitals.
</P>
<P>
The government plan for reforming NHS has be welcomed by
doctors, nurses and union chiefs, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
The British Medical Association said the new plans were driven
by patients needs and were positive in improving health services.
</P>
</TEXT>
