<HEADLINE> S.Korea May Restrict Arms Purchases Because of Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- South Korea may restrict its
arms purchases because of a recent economic crisis but will not
reduce its financial support for 37,000 U.S. troops there, South
Korean Defense Minister Kim Dong-jin said today.
</P>
<P>
"Because of the forthcoming tight budget, I feel there will be
some restrictions on the purchase of foreign weapons and exchange
of personnel between our countries," Kim said at a joint news
conference with U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen after their
annual bilateral security talks, called the Security Constructive
Meeting, at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
"Although it is true that the Korean government is having
difficulties with its economy, I do not feel it will affect the
alliance structure that we have between our two countries," he
added with regard to housing and other support for U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
When asked about four-party peace talks on the Korean
Peninsula, now convening in Geneva with the participation of the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea, South Korea, the United
States and China, Kim declined to make any predictions at an early
stage, saying "the fundamental purpose of the four-party talks is
to have a long-term, stable peace agreement along the Korean
Peninsula."
</P>
<P>
Cohen also made cautious remarks, saying the talks were "not
something we look at in terms of spontaneous or very quick
solutions to a long-standing problem."
</P>
<P>
The annual Security Constructive Meeting was originally
scheduled to be held in Seoul last month during Cohen's planned
visit to Asia. But as Cohen postponed his trip because of a
weapons inspection crisis in Iraq, the venue has been shifted to
Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
